<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Parties to Adopt Bipartisan Approach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's ruling People's
Alliance (PA) and the opposition United National Party (UNP) have
agreed to adopt a bipartisan approach towards the resolution of
the ethnic conflict, Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar
announced here tonight.
</P>
<P>
"The president and the leader of the opposition had exchanged
letters about a number of arrangements which are intended to
develop a common, cross-party approach - a bipartisan approach
towards the resolution of the ethnic conflict in the country,"
Kadirgamar said.
</P>
<P>
"The need to restore peace was of overwhelming importance, for
progress in other areas in the country and for the prosperity of
the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a need which transcends party politics. There can be no
doubt that a great many of Sri Lankans irrespective of political
persuasion, share this view and believe that efforts should be
made to develop common approaches towards the resolution of the
conflict," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the understanding between the parties was an important
and valuable step to help resolve a vital issue. "It deserved to
be welcomed widely by the people and by the friends of Sri Lanka."
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
