<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, April 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- British opposition Labor Party launched its manifesto
Thursday, promising not to raise income tax rates, guarantee low
inflation, create jobs and put education the number one priority
if it wins the May 1 election.
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU -- At least five people were killed and eight others
wounded when clan fighting broke out between militiamen from
Hawadle and Galjel clans at Burane village, 113 kilometers north
of Mogadishu on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl Thursday told a German
television that he plans to seek reelection in the general
elections in 1998. "I will run because I believe that I have an
obligation to do this in the current situation. We are facing
difficult international developments," Kohl said in an interview
with Germany's ARD television network.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli government issued a statement Thursday
announcing what it called a suspension in "its request to
extradite Hamas leader Mussa Abu Marzook to Israel."
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- The Japanese government Thursday approved a bill at a
special meeting to give the green light for the continued land use
by the U.S. military forces in Okinawa, a southern island of Japan.
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- A helicopter belonging to the Thai navy crashed this
morning, seriously injuring a deputy commander-in-chief of the
Thai navy. The helicopter developed an engine fault only one
minute after it took off at an airstrip in western Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A senior Palestinian official denied Thursday
reports that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat planned to meet with
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu in Washington this week.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's foreign debts totaled 104.5 billion
U.S. dollars at the end of 1996, 33.3 percent more than that of
the previous year, the Bank of Korea (BOK) said Thursday. 
</P>
