<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl to Run for Reelection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- After a record 15 years in office,
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today revealed his plan to seek
another four-year term in the 1998 general election.
</P>
<P>
"I will run because I believe that I have an obligation to do
this in the current situation," Kohl said in an interview with
Germany's ARD television network.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing difficult international developments," Kohl said
while celebrating his 67th birthday at an Austrian spa in Bad
Hofgastein. It is the first time he made clear his intentions to
run for a fifth term.
</P>
<P>
Having been in office since 1982, Kohl is currently the longest
serving leader in major Western countries. He oversaw some of the
most indelible developments of the country, including the 1990
unification.
</P>
<P>
But his popularity has been declining recently as the country
suffers a post-war record unemployment and a sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll conducted by the RTL television network today
showed that 67.5 percent of the some 60,000 people asked were
against Kohl running again in October, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) said today
that it would name its candidates for chancellor in April next
year as planned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
