<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU "Anxious" for Middle East Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union was as anxious
as anyone for Middle East peace, but a lasting settlement was a
matter for Israel and the Palestinians, the European Commission
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It would be useful and acceptable for our role to be enhanced,
but so far only one side has asked for it," said Josep Coll i
Carbo, spokesman for Manuel Marin, the European Commissioner
responsible for Middle East affairs.
</P>
<P>
Coll i Carbo made the remarks at a news briefing when asked
whether there might be a European initiative following calls by
the Arab League for a greater EU role in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said the issue was certain to be raised during a meeting of
EU and Mediterranean foreign ministers in Malta later this month.
</P>
<P>
The meeting -- which will include Israel -- will go ahead
despite a pledge by the Arab League on Monday to freeze relations
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arab-Israeli relations have plummeted since Israel started
building a Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Ministers from the 15 EU member countries and the south
Mediterranean, including Egypt, Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Morocco,
Tunisia, Algeria, the Palestinian Authority and Israel are due to
meet in Malta on April 15 and 16 to assess progress in the
Euro-Med Partnership agreed in Barcelona, Spain, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Hopes are growing that the European Union might at last play a
key role as a broker to save the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The EU's influence is underpinned by the fact that it accounts
for 53 percent of foreign aid to the Palestinian Authority and is
Israel's biggest trading partner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
