<HEADLINE> 1938 Munich Treaty "Shameful Resignation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac said
today that the 1938 Munich Treaty signed by France and Britain to
let Hitler's Germany grasp one part of Czechoslovakia is a
"shameful resignation of democracy."
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the two chambers of the Czech parliament in
Prague, Chirac said that Europe should draw a lesson from it,
which he said had "thrown the entire Europe into darkness,"
according to Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
"For all one generation of mine, this shameful resignation of
democracy is considered as its greatest error. It threw the entire
Europe into darkness and tragedies. We should, for Europe, draw a
lesson from it," he said.
</P>
<P>
France and Britain signed the treaty to appease Nazi Germany
and fascist Italy, in the German Bavarian city on September 30,
1938, allowing Germany to annex one part of Czechslovakia at a
time when world fascist forces were starting World War II.
</P>
<P>
Queen Elizabeth II of Britain made an apology to Prague when
she visited the Czech Republic in March 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Reaffirms French Demand for NATO's European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today reaffirmed France's demand for the building of a European
identity of defense in the NATO Southern Command, which he said is
the precondition for the return of France to NATO's integrated
military command, according to Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
"If the reform of NATO allows Europe to assume a responsibility
permitting the definition of a European identity of defense,
France is ready to adhere," said Chirac at a press conference in
the Czech Republic where he was making a visit.
</P>
<P>
He said that he cannot give a final answer to the question of
whether France and the United States can resolve their dispute
over the Europeanization of NATO's Southern Command, and that the
two countries are continuing their talks "in the best spirit."
</P>
<P>
"If, to the contrary, it is for the reasons that I perfectly
understand and which don't make up any problem between the United
States and France, the Americans can maintain their complete
control of NATO, and France will remain in its present situation,"
said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
France now maintains a single membership of NATO while
remaining independent of the NATO trans-Atlantic integrated
military command structure dominated by the United States.
</P>
<P>
On the NATO Madrid summit to be held in July, Chirac said that
he is "very optimistic" about the result the summit can obtain and
that France does not have any difference with the United States
over the timing and agenda of the summit.
</P>
<P>
He said that reform of NATO "could be finalized and ended in
Madrid." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
