<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pictorial Biography of Deng Xiaoping Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- "Deng Xiaoping and Modern China,"
a pictorial biography of China's late senior leader, has been
published in both Chinese and English by the Modern Publishing
House.
</P>
<P>
With nine chapters and 150,000 Chinese characters, the book
includes over 500 pictures recalling Deng's contributions to China
and the Chinese people in his 70-plus years of revolutionary
activities.
</P>
<P>
A clear-cut image of Deng is presented in the book: as a young
man, he went abroad to seek ways to help China; as a soldier, he
fought in a number of places; as a staunch Party member, he was
indomitable; as a statesman, he worked out a blueprint for China;
and as an old man, he was affectionate toward his family.
</P>
<P>
The authors also wrote a widely-popular 12-part documentary on
Deng which was first televised in January in China.
</P>
<P>
The book was revised five times in the past three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Companies Urged to Practice Self-Intellectual Rights Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese companies and institutions
shouldn't just bury their heads in scientific research, they must
also learn how to protect their intellectual rights in today's
competitive market economy, state councillor Song Jian stressed
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of delegates from 45 companies and
institutions, including the Beijing Founder Group and Qinghua
University, Song said that China has established a basic legal
framework for intellectual rights protection, which includes the
newly-revised criminal law containing strict punishment for
violators.
</P>
<P>
But because China has yet to establish competent law enforcing
organizations in the area of intellectual rights protection,
companies and institutions for the time being have to learn how to
protect themselves and leave no areas vulnerable to intellectual
rights violation, Song said.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized the importance of intellectual rights
protection for China's own famous-brand goods in the world.
Chinese officials and economists recently have been calling on
companies to publicize this issue more widely and also to improve
the quality of their goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
