<HEADLINE> Hong Kong-based Collegiate Joint Venture Eyes China Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- An Australian College has joined
in a Hong Kong university to offer distance-learning business
courses to pave the way for future operations in the Chinese
inland areas.
</P>
<P>
A further education and training college, the Open Learning
Institute of Technical And Further Education (TAFE) based in
Queensland, Australia, joined in the Hong Kong College of
Technology International (HKCTI) in operating the four business
diploma courses now offered in the Hong Kong college.
</P>
<P>
And the two colleges wish to introduce the courses in the
Chinese inland areas.
</P>
<P>
"Both the Institute and the HKCTI are interested in exploring
the China market," HKCTI program development executive Flora Chan
Kit-ching was quoted by English-language newspaper South China
Morning Post today as saying.
</P>
<P>
HKCTI is now the sole Hong Kong examination center for China's
government-administered self-study High Education Examination.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Federation of Hong Kong Industries and
Executive Councilor of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
Henry Tang Ying-yen applauded the event. "This event highlights
two key elements which are vital to the future development of
business in Hong Kong. The first is education and the second is
collaboration," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There are many examples in Hong Kong of companies teaming up
with others around the world to offer customers the best possible
service or product, like the establishment of manufacturing joint
ventures.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to see that concept being similarly applied to
education," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
