<HEADLINE> Rebel Alliance Rejects Offer of Zaire Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Alliance of Democratic
Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL) today rejected an
offer of six ministries to join a government headed by zaire's
new Premier Etienne Tshisekedi, a report from Goma said.
</P>
<P>
Raphael Nghenda, ADFL Information Commissioner, told reporters
as he boarded a plane in the eastern Zairean town of Goma for the
talks in South Africa that his alliance would not accept the
posts reserved by Tshisekedi for them.
</P>
<P>
He boarded the plane in the company of Bizima Karaha, Foreign
Affairs Commissioner for the ADFL which led the rebellion to
fight to topple President Mobutu Sese Seko in eastern Zaire last
October.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today Tshisekedi unveiled a 26-member cabinet in
Kinshasa with no associates of President Mobutu and six
ministries reserved for the rebel alliance in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Tshisekedi, addressing a news conference on the formation of
his new government, said portfolios of foreign affairs, defense,
budget, planning, foreign trade and agriculture were reserved for
the rebel alliance.
</P>
<P>
However, the rebels have said they would not negotiate with
Tshisekedi as prime minister and would only deal directly with
Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
Tshisekedi today praised Laurent Kabila, whose rebels have
seized a quarter of Zaire and are targeting mainstay mining
centers after taking up arms to fight from the Rwandan border in
October.
</P>
<P>
``Kabila has contributed to the return of legality. He merits
the acclaim of our people,'' Tshisekedi said, trying to lure
kabila into making contact with him.
</P>
<P>
But he said the civil war now had to stop.
</P>
<P>
Nghenda and Karaha later left for South Africa for the first
face-to-face negotiations with an eight-member Zairean government
delegation led by Honore Ngbanda, Mobutu's security adviser.
</P>
</TEXT>
