<HEADLINE> World Bank Okays Credit for Sri Lanka's Environmental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today announced
the approval of a 14.8 million U.S. dollar credit to help finance
the Sri Lanka government's Environmental Action I Project.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to support the government's efforts to
strengthen its institutional and policy framework for
environmental management and take immediate measures to reverse
the southern Asian country's trend of environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
The project will support the restructuring of the Environment
Department within Sri Lanka's Ministry of Transport, Environment
and Women's Affairs so it can play a central role in environmental
policy, planning, and coordination at the national level. It will
also help develop a policy action plan which will broadly define
the legal and policy changes necessary for sound environmental
management.
</P>
<P>
The total project cost is estimated at 20.7 million dollars. In
addition to the World Bank's credit which will be channeled
through the International Development Association (IDA)--- the
World Bank's concessional lending wing, the government of Sri
Lanka will provide 3.4 million dollars and local communities 2.5
million dollars which will be mainly provided in labor and
material. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
