<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National AIDS Code Formulated in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- An inter-sectoral committee
comprising government, employers and trade unions has formulated
a national code of practice on AIDS and employment which, among
other things, forbids HIV testing for employment purposes.
</P>
<P>
The code, which is now before the Attorney General, is to
cover all public and private sector work places, including export
processing zones and diplomatic missions.
</P>
<P>
According to the preamble of the code, released at a meeting
of the inter-sectoral committee on AIDS today, an employee with
HIV should be treated the same way as any other healthy employee
while a worker with AIDS had to be treated as any other with a
life threatening illness.
</P>
<P>
The code forbids compulsory HIV testing in work places while
direct pre-employment testing would also not be allowed.
</P>
<P>
The code is a result of over two years of consultations
between the Ministry of Public Service, Labor and Social Welfare,
the Employers Confederation of Zimbabwe and the Zimbabwe Congress
of Trade Unions and will be incorporated into the Labor Relations
Act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Reform Securities Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The German government today proposed
revised securities laws and expected the new legislation could run
from next year before the planned 1999 introduction of the
European single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
The 100 reforms proposed to Germany's present securities laws
would among other things facilitate money raising by foreign
companies on the country's financial market, according to Juergen
Stark, state secretary for finance.
</P>
<P>
For example, foreign-language prospectuses would be allowed
under some circumstances according to the new rules, in comparison
with current provisions that demand German version of prospectuses
from all foreign issuers.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the new laws okay new derivatives including
interest-rate and foreign-exchange swaps.
</P>
<P>
The revisions raise the maximum penalty for issuing fraudulent
prospectuses to 1 million marks (600,000 US dollars) from the
current 100,000 marks, while easing the punishment for false
statements in company prospectuses and reports -- the court would
have three years instead of five years to charge offenders.
</P>
</TEXT>
