<HEADLINE> PAC Makes Disciplinary Decision Against Makwetu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Pan Africanist Congress
(PAC) of South Africa today reached finality about possible
disciplinary steps against its former president Clarence Makwetu,
but PAC officials declined to reveal what the decision was.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at an internal disciplinary committee
hearing at PAC's Pretoria office earlier in the day without
attendance of Makwetu.
</P>
<P>
Makwetu is facing three charges relating to allegations that
he has divided the party, created factions, and has violated the
PAC's oath of allegiance which states that a member will accept
party leadership.
</P>
<P>
PAC insiders said it was believed the committee had
recommended that Makwetu, now national chairman, be expelled from
the organization.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials said, however, the finding of the
disciplinary hearing would be referred to the party's National
Executive Committee (NEC) for approval. The NEC was scheduled to
meet in Soweto on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Makwetu, who earlier confirmed he would attend the hearing,
did not show up at the hearing charging him of violating the
party's constitution. He spent the day in "his fields" in Eastern
Cape Province instead.
</P>
<P>
Makwetu lost the presidency to former Methodist Bishop Stanley
Mogoba at the PAC's national conference in December last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Makwetu's supporters claim the elections were
unconstitutional and have refused to recognize the party's new
leadership, thus causing an internal strife and rival factions.
</P>
</TEXT>
