<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Ruling Party Infiltrated: Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- ZANU (PF) National Chairman Joseph
Msika today charged that Zimbabwe's ruling party has been
infiltrated by some agents bent on discrediting it with the
public.
</P>
<P>
Msika asserted here that the party's leadership is now in the
process of identifying and weeding out undesirable elements
tarnishing the image of ZANU (PF), which has ruled the country
since independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
''There are people who tried to organize their own party to
oppose ZANU (PF) and when they found that ZANU (PF) was very
strong, they resorted to the expression that if you cannot defeat
them, then join them and fight them from within,'' Msika said.
</P>
<P>
He said some of the infiltrators had used money to buy their
way into the party or employed some unscrupulous means to
hoodwink either the district or provincial leadership of ZANU
(PF).
</P>
<P>
Some, he went on, had even gained entry into the central
committee.
</P>
<P>
''Those that are found committing acts of indiscipline will be
severely dealt with by way of punishing them through suspension.
If they prove to be incorrigible, as a last resort it would be
expulsion from the party,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
