<HEADLINE> Germany Rejects Turkey's Accusations Over Arson Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The German government today said it
was "astonished" and "disappointed" at the recent accusations by
Turkey that Germany tolerates human rights abuses against Muslims,
news reports said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's ambassador to Germany, Volkan Vural, was summoned to
the German Foreign Ministry today and was given a letter as a
reaction to the accusations made by Turkish Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
"It is not acceptable that official Turkish positions take part
in prejudgement, unsubstantiated accusations and attacks on the
German government," the German news agency DPA quoted the letter
as saying.
</P>
<P>
After nine Turkish nationals were killed in arson attacks in
Germany and the Netherlands during the past week, Erbakan
reportedly accused Western European leaders of tolerating such
anti-Islamic activities.
</P>
<P>
"You take the people who perpetrate these horrors and release
them three days later so they can roam free as a bird again. That
is nothing less than condoning their behavior," one of them said.
</P>
<P>
So far, authorities in both Germany and the Netherlands have
failed to find out the motives behind the arson attacks.
</P>
<P>
The fire broke out in a Turkish family's apartment early Monday
at the western German city of Krefeld, killing a 41-year-old
Turkish woman and her 19-year-old daughter when they jumped from a
third-floor window to escape. The woman's 17-year-old son died of
smoke inhalation inside the apartment.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish community in Germany has called for a quick
clarification of the incident while the Turkish ambassador in Bonn
said in an interview with a German television after the incident
that xenophobia and racist attacks are a "reality in Germany."
</P>
</TEXT>
