<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Ranks Low in World Health Study: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain ranks 15th in a world
health survey of 27 countries and is among the unhealthiest places
to live in Western Europe, according to a latest world health
study.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by The Economist Intelligence Unit, uses
12 indicators of public health to judge each nation's physical
wellbeing, which included immunization rates, maternal mortality,
HIV, infant mortality, and rates of cancer, heart disease and
respiratory disease per head of population, as well as life
expectancy.
</P>
<P>
Although Britain has respectable figures for average life
expectancy, bad diet and a high number of deaths from cancer and
circulatory diseases put the country behind Mexico and Israel in
the league table.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that Sweden is the healthiest place in the
world and has the best medical practice. Israel is the second best
place to avoid being ill. South Africa is the least healthy place,
with India, Brazil and Russia in the places just above it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, health care in the United States, which is 13th in
the league table, is also at a low ebb. The study blamed this on
the increasing numbers in the US who no longer have any medical
insurance and cannot afford to pay for medical care.
</P>
<P>
It said that 45 million people, roughly 16 percent of the
country's population are expected to be uninsured by the turn of
the century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
