<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EMU Timetable to Top EU Finance Ministers Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- European Union finance ministers
and central bankers will meet this weekend in Noordwijk, the
Netherlands, to swap views on the different 1998 timetable seeking
to determine the list of countries that will be joining the single
currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
"The main objective (of the informal meeting) will be to give
further impetus to the preparation of the third and final stage of
Economic and Monetary Union (EMU)," the Dutch EU presidency said in
a statement today.
</P>
<P>
Disturbed by widespread speculation in recent weeks about a
delay in the starting date for the Euro, the EU finance ministers,
however, are expected to reaffirm their commitment to the 1999
deadline.
</P>
<P>
Even though a number of issues concerning the technical aspects
of EMU will be on the table at the weekend gathering, such details
are anticipated by some experts to be forced to take a back seat
to the more pressing concerns of sluggish EU growth, rising
unemployment and the battle that many EU governments are having in
meeting the precondition for EMU, scheduled to start on January 1,
1999.
</P>
<P>
More attention will be drawn on Germany, which is facing record
unemployment and doubts over the speed at which its economy will
expand in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Countries wishing to join EMU must meet various criteria set
out in the Maastricht treaty on deficits, debt, inflation,interest
rates and exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
Prior to March 1, 1998, each member state is required to
provide the European Commission with final information on the
country's 1997 budget performance.
</P>
<P>
The commission and the European Monetary Institute, the
forerunner of the future European Central Bank, will then have
roughly two weeks to come up with their convergence reports.
</P>
<P>
After the evaluation, there is a six-week consultation period
with the European Parliament, before a qualified majority decision
will be taken, at a meeting of heads of state and government of
the EU countries, to adopt the list of countries due to join the
Euro on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
While a precise date might not be set in Noordwijk, the
logistics of the EU decision-making process suggests a late-April
timetable, a commission official said.
</P>
<P>
In the seaside town of Noordwijk, the ministers will also
receive an update on negotiations to put a stability and growth
pact into a legal context.
</P>
<P>
The pact, which seeks to penalize governments running excessive
budget deficit -- above 3 percent of GDP -- inside EMU, was agreed
last December after lengthy and often tense negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The group will also take stock of negotiations on a revamped
Exchange Rate Mechanism, dubbed ERM 2, and designed to link
countries outside EMU to the Euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unclear Rules Dog European Tender Process: Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Rules for tendering maintenance
contracts in the European Union are often unclear and interpreted
in different ways, according to a recent research carried out for
the Dutch state building service Rijksgebouwdienst.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said either the European Commission should
clarify the rules or European jurisprudence should be adapted as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Under the rules, EU member states have to tender out
maintenance projects whenever the cost goes over a given limit.
</P>
<P>
In the case of the Netherlands, they said, this has meant that
114 contracts with a total value of almost 10.5 million US dollars
a year have been put out to tender.
</P>
<P>
However, various contractors' organizations in the Netherlands
have protested about the strict, and complicated, way the EU
directives have been interpreted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
