<HEADLINE> Major Blames IRA for Bombs on British Motorway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- British police found a suspect
package of explosives today which was planted on one of the
country's major motorways.
</P>
<P>
Although no group claimed responsibility for the attempted
bombing, Prime Minister John Major blamed the Irish Republican
Army (IRA) for the incident.
</P>
<P>
"It was intended deliberately to cause trouble, and it looks as
though it was the IRA playing silly games," Major told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"I think most people know what the IRA are and see them for
what they are," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Reuters news agency quoted a local police spokesman as
saying the advice they have from bomb disposal experts "is that
the device was a viable bomb which, if it had gone off, could have
caused considerable damage and possible loss of life as well."
</P>
<P>
At the height of the morning rush hour, police received coded
telephone calls warning of bombs in various sections of motorways
in central England. A Defense Ministry's bomb squad was sent
immediately to a motorway bridge where a suspect package was
found.
</P>
<P>
Mo Mowlam, the Northern Ireland spokeswoman for the opposition
Labor party, also blamed the IRA.
</P>
<P>
"Labor deplores this action by the IRA. The IRA... must
understand a new Labor government would oppose tooth and nail the
use of violent and terrorist methods for political ends," she
said. 
