<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Parties Meet in Athens to Discuss Albania Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Greece, Albania, the European Union
(EU) and the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE) today agreed in their talks here that the international
community will coordinate their actions in restoring peace and
stability in the strife-ridden Albania.
</P>
<P>
The talks were attended by visiting Albanian Prime Minister
Bashkim Fino, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos, Dutch
Foreign Minister Hans Van Mierlo, whose country is currently
holding the rotating EU presidency, and OSCE special envoy for
Albania Franz Vranitsky, former Austrian chancellor.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after the talks, Foreign
Minister Pangalos said that the solidarity of the international
community in restoring peace and stability in Tirana was
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Vranitsky set out three aspects of action
planned by the international community. These were the
distribution of humanitarian and economic aid, to be directed by
the EU; the establishment and protection of democracy and human
rights, including the June elections, to be coordinated by the
OSCE; and the international peace force, to be undertaken by
Italy.
</P>
<P>
Fino emphasized during the talks that the June elections would
be fair and democratic and would be held with the support of the
OSCE and the EU.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos said that Albania had requested during the talks that
the multinational force to be dispatched to Albania not be divided
into national contingents but rather be composed of mixed units,
and the Greek side had agreed to Tirana's position.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the "interlocutor" of the international
community in Tirana was of course the Albanian government.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that during Wednesday's talks, Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis proposed and Fino accepted the
strengthening of the international community's "institutional pole
of action in Albania."
</P>
<P>
As for the deployment of the multinational force in Albania, he
said that Athens did not insist that the 700 Greek contingent be
stationed in southern Albania, where about 300,000 ethnic Greek
minority live, because Athens was exercising a policy of
friendship and cooperation which took into consideration the
entire Albanian people, Pangalos said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Greece was implementing the same policy in the
Balkans in general, aimed at creating relations "which look
forward not backwards."
</P>
<P>
The primary aspiration of Greek foreign policy was to safeguard
the inviolability of borders, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the target was "not to go beyond the end
of next week." He was referring to the date of the multinational
force to be sent to Albania.
</P>
<P>
Fino, Hans van Mierlo and Vranitsky arrived here Wednesday for
talks with the Greek government to discuss ways of solving the
crisis in Albania, particularly in the deployment of the
multinational force and the economic assistance to be given to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
Fino is expected to leave here for Tirana later today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
