<HEADLINE> OIC: Jerusalem Core of Arab-Israeli Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Jerusalem, the holy city to
Muslims, Jews and Christians alike, is the core of the
Arab-Israeli conflict, Secretary General of the Organization of
the Islamic Conference (OIC) Abdel Aziz Ghoush said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking from Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, in a telephone interview
with the Egypt's Voice of the Arab, he said the Islamic world can
not accept anything which impairs their right in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"Any solution that does not secure rights in Jerusalem is
deficient and unacceptable on the Islamic level," he said.
</P>
<P>
He accused Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu of
killing the Mideast peace process by sending bulldozers to Jabal
Abu Ghneim, or Har Homa, to build the 6,500-unit Jewish
neighborhood in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The major resolutions issued by the Islamabad Islamic summit,
the Jerusalem Committee of the OIC and the Arab League Council
meetings are natural reactions against Israel's policy that aims
at imposing a status quo in the Holy city, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the U.S. to play its role as main sponsor of the
peace process and spare the area the violence which is not in the
interests of any party.
</P>
<P>
"This is possible through making Israel implement the principle
of land for peace and the international legitimacy resolutions,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Following the U.S. double veto last month in the U.N. Security
Council of moves to condemn Israel's settlement project, the
Islamic and Arab countries launched an intensive campaign to halt
what they view the Judaization attempt on Jerusalem by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs decided to stop normal relations with Israel, revive
economic boycott, close down Israeli missions and withdraw from
Mideast multilateral talks in a resolution approved by the Arab
League Council meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, wanting to establish a capital in East
Jerusalem, accused Israel of sabotaging the peace process by
building a Jewish housing project on disputed Arab land and
tempering the Islamic features of the holy city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
