<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnia Peace Monitoring Committee Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A two-day meeting of the Bosnia
Peace Monitoring Committee ended today in Istanbul, the largest
city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after the meeting, Carl Bildt,
High Representative responsible for the implementation of Dayton
Agreement's civilian issues, said that "I believe that peace will
be installed gradually to the region."
</P>
<P>
Two decisions were taken at the Steering Committee meeting,
said Bildt, adding that the first is to set up "City
Administration" and the second advises Serbs, living in Croatia's
"Eastern Slovenia" region, not to evacuate the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Steering Committee is ready to extend any
contribution to peace, adding that the parties concerned should
make efforts to this end.
</P>
<P>
"Establishing joint institutions and providing developments on
economic issues" are the main problems in Bosnia-Herzegovina,
said Bildt.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Foreign Ministry deputy undersecretary Ali
Tuygan, who attended the meeting, said that Turkey is interested
in peace and stability in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
He said that "Turkey is the most important country among
Muslim countries which may play a role in providing peace and
stability in the Balkans."  
</P>
</TEXT>
