<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Desalination Plant Inaugurated in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
today inaugurated the island's first desalination plant in a major
step to tackle the country's chronic fresh water shortage problem.
</P>
<P>
The desalination plant, constructed near the Dhekelia electric
power station on the island's southeastern coast, will meet the
increased demand for water in the country's burgeoning tourist
areas in the Famagusta District, eastern part of the island.
</P>
<P>
The plant is capable, at maximum capacity, of converting
40,000 cubic meters of sea water into drinking water, which meets
the strict European standards.
</P>
<P>
"This project takes on a heightened importance due to the
continual water shortage we face," Clerides said at the
inauguration ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He added "the water problem is something that concerns all of
us, the public and the state. We are compelled to deal with this
problem diligently and insistently, because our economic and
social progress depends on it."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has suffered severe droughts throughout its history,
including this year's continuous drought, due to the lack of rain
and a shortage of rivers running all year-round.
</P>
<P>
Presently, the agricultural sector, as well as most villages
and towns, depend on the Cyprus' damming network which can hold
up to 300 million cubic meters of water.
</P>
<P>
"A strategic plan for water needs has been drawn up by the
government to cover the period up to the year 2010," the
president said, adding that the government plans, beyond
constructing new dams and desalination plants, are to engender a
public conscience for conserving water.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that when government measures kick into gear,
about 95 to 100 million cubic meters of water will be added to the
island's reserves.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the Cypriot government adopted strict
measures to save fresh water as the island's water reserves
are currently at the lowest level since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Since January, water supply to the households in the country
has been reduced by 20 percent, with water supply provided only
three days a week. Water for farming purposes has also been
decreased by up to 70 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
