<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Against Turkish Violation of Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Ministry has
protested to the United Nations over the recent violations of
the Cypriot air space by Turkish military aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing here today, government
spokesman Yiannakis Cassoulides cited Cyprus National Guard
information as saying that one reconnaissance plane and
squadrons of Turkish fighters have violated Cyprus' sovereign air
space and the Nicosia Flight Information Region (FIR) on five
different occasions in the past ten days.
</P>
<P>
On March 27, he noted, a reconnaissance aircraft, RF-4,
approached the island's northern coast, violating the Nicosia
FIR. He added that on March 31 there were two violations of the
Republic's air space and Nicosia's FIR, and another two
violations on April 1.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military aircraft also entered the Cyprus'
northern air space and flew over the Turkish-occupied northern
areas, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"These facts constitute a violation of international law and
are accordingly protested to the U.N. by the Foreign Ministry,"
Cassoulides said, adding that "they are not conducive to the
climate which should exist in the on-going negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that despite these violations "our side
will continue its constructive stance during the proximity
talks." But he noted that President Glafcos Clerides will raise
the issue during his meeting Friday with U.N. Resident
Representative Gustave Feissel.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led proximity talks, during which Feissel has
bi-weekly separate meetings with Cypriot President Glafcos
clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, have entered
into their third week.
</P>
<P>
The talks are aimed at breaking the current deadlock on
Cyprus problem and paving the way for the U.N. proposed direct
negotiations between the leaders of the two community during the
first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has indicated that it wants to see both sides make
"goodwill gestures" to improve the climate for the talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot south and the
Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an Athens-backed
coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
