<HEADLINE> UN Envoy to Visit Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Chief's special
representative for Cyprus Han Sung Joo will begin a week-long
visit to Cyprus on April 12 in a bid to help start face-to-face
negotiations between Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government spokesman Yiannakis Cassoulides said here
today that the Cypriot government welcomes Han's visit to Cyprus
aimed at breaking the deadlock in efforts to reach a solution to
the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has
announced that the U.N. representative will then visit Ankara and
Athens for talks on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, the Cypriot spokesman
said that Han is expected "at a crucial period in the proximity
talks" between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides conducted by
U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave Feissel.
</P>
<P>
He added that "it is logical that after three to four weeks of
talks the time would be appropriate for the U.N. to review the
situation and redirect their course accordingly."
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored proximity talks, during which Feissel has
bi-weekly separate meetings with Clerides and Denktash, have
entered into their third week. However, nothing has been revealed
about the talks which began on March 10.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the two communities have not met since October
1994.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. is stepping up efforts so that direct negotiations
for a solution to the Cyprus problem could begin by the middle
of this year.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Annan will meet Denktash in Geneva,
Switzerland, on April 9, prior to Han's visit to the region.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
