<HEADLINE> Muslim-Croat Joint Police to Patrol Mostar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A Muslim-Croat joint police will
start patroling central Mostar Friday after both sides agreed on
the law enforcement formation, an international official said
today.
</P>
<P>
The first shift of the joint police will begin at 4:00 am local
time, with 10 policemen from each side and under the supervision
of the UN International Police Task Force (IPTF), said Alexander
Ivanko, spokesman for the IPTF.
</P>
<P>
The agreed joint force for the central district of Mostar will
consist of 100 police officers, 50 from each side, and is part of
the initiative to unify police forces in the Herzegovina-Neretva
canton of the Muslim-Croat federation by the middle of this month.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations on the joint force have been difficult, especially
after the February 10 incident in which Croat policemen were
accused of killing one Muslim and wounding 20 others who were
visiting family graveyards in the Croat-controlled area.
</P>
<P>
Although both sides finally agreed on joint patrols in the
central district of Mostar, there still exist some minor
differences and the agreement has not been signed by both sides,
the IPTF said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
