<HEADLINE> France Official: Turkey Has Right to Enter EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has the right to be a full
member of the European Union (EU) like other candidate countries,
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said here
today.
</P>
<P>
But he said that Turkey has to abide by economic, political and
human rights criterions to realize this.
</P>
<P>
Rummelhardt made the remarks after French Foreign Minister
Herve De Charette met with Turkish Parliament Speaker Mustafa
Kalemli, Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki Karadayi and other
political party leaders.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was greatly angered by a March 4 statement by the EU
Christian Democrats who called Turkey's membership application
unacceptable due to its religious culture.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with Turkish main opposition Motherland Party
(ANAP) Chairman Mesut Yilmaz, De Charette said that his visit took
place at a very important time regarding projects between Turkey
and France and Turkish-European ties.
</P>
<P>
De Charette, who arrived here Wednesday evening for a two-day
official visit to Turkey, also told Bulent Ecevit, chairman of the
Democratic Left Party (DSP), that "Turkey and France are the two
important powers in the Mediterranean and called for joint efforts
to be extended to turn Mediterranean basin into a region of peace
and stability."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, during his meeting with De Charette Wednesday,
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel said that Europe can not be
thought without Turkey and Turkey can not be thought without
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Demirel also expressed gratitude to France for its support for
Turkey's bid to be admitted into the EU.
</P>
<P>
Before her official talks with De Charette Wednesday, Turkish
Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller
reiterated that she wanted Turkey to be judged on equal terms
with other countries.
</P>
<P>
For his part, De Charette said "France clearly believes that
Turkey has potential to take part in the building of Europe."
</P>
