<HEADLINE> Irish Government Likely to Call Early Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Ireland's three-party coalition
government is likely to call an early election in mid-May as its
popularity gap with opposition parties narrowed, according to
reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
The MRBI poll, carried in today's Irish Times newspaper,
revealed that Prime Minister John Bruton's coalition, including
Fine Gael, Labor and Democratic Left, was trailing opposition
parties by six percentage points in comparison with a 12-point gap
in a similar poll conducted in January.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that 43 percent of those questioned would
prefer a Fianna Fail and Progressive Democrat coalition and 37
percent the current ruling group compared to 44 and 32 percent
respectively in the January survey.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said that this latest opinion poll was
likely to encourage Bruton to call an early election in a bid to
profit from a tax reduction budget in January and a wave of job
creation, although the general election is not due until November.
</P>
<P>
Bruton is expected to call a cabinet meeting next Tuesday to
discuss the exact polling date and election experts predicted that
the election would probably be held towards the end of May or in
early June.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the survey showed that Irish voters were
becoming more and more concerned with crimes, which have overtaken
unemployment as the main election issue.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said that there had been a sharp worrying
increase in organized crime and worsening drug problems as drug
abuse increased dramatically across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
