<HEADLINE> European Shares down on Weak Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe all
sustained their recent decline and ended sharply lower Thursday,
depressed by Wall Street's retreat, fresh worries about higher
interest rates and the dollar's weakness.
</P>
<P>
British shares in London, although suffered heavy losses early
in the day following the Dow's overnight drop, stood up well in
later trading, with the FTSE 100 index ending 22.0 points lower at
4,214.6.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that gains in utility stocks and hopes that UK
gilts will outperform their US counterparts helped drag the market
back up from its early lows.
</P>
<P>
However, there was little doubt that stocks were vulnerable to
moves in New York.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares closed the day with heavy losses
after Wall Street jitters undermined the market and traders said
that share prices will continue to take their cue from New York
ahead of the release of all-important US jobs figures on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index finished the session down 86.67 points at
3,215.24.
</P>
<P>
The Paris bourse closed weaker for the third day running, with
the CAC-40 index 15.76 points lower at 2,514.52, undermined by
fresh losses on Wall Street, lower domestic bonds and weaker
dollar.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares ended down
22.0 points at 4,214.6. In Frankfurt, the DAX-30 index closed
86.67 points down at 3,215.24. The Paris CAC-40 index finished
15.76 points weaker at 2,514.52.  
</P>
