<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Fraud Uncovered in New York City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A stock fraud has been uncovered
in New York City with 18 residents of five states charged on
Wednesday with operating a scheme that bilked investors out of
millions of U.S. dollars, the New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
A ring, made up largely of Russian emigres from the states of
</P>
<P>
New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Oregon and Florida, used
high-pressure sales tactics and gross misrepresentations in
pitching the stock of a company called Globus Group Inc. through
telephone calls to people across the United States.
</P>
<P>
Persuaded by such pitches, at least 800 investors bought Globus
shares between January and September of last year, pushing the
price up 8 dollars a share from 25 cents, and members of the ring
sold, at the higher prices, thousands of shares they secretly
held, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Investors lost five million to eight million U.S. dollars in
the fraud. With at least 800 people having been bilked, the
average would be 6,000 to 10,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The indictment was the latest action by law enforcement
officials and securities regulators against stock fraud. 
</P>
</TEXT>
