<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Holds Forum on Global Biodiversity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A two-day international
forum is held at United Nations headquarters to identify concrete
targets and specific measurements of progress for addressing the
urgent global problem of the loss of biological diversity.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, known as the Global Biodiversity Forum beginning
today, involved about 100 participants from over 30 countries,
United Nations Environment Program, the United Nations Development
Program and the World Bank, leading non-governmental organizations
and scientific institutions.
</P>
<P>
UN reported that the earth's biodiversity is being lost at a
rate unprecedented in human history, due to an onslaught of human
activities leading to the loss, degradation and fragmentation of
natural habitats and the over-exploitation of living resources,
among other threats.
</P>
<P>
To respond to this crisis, the Convention on Biological
Diversity was signed by most of the world's governments at the
Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The forum will focus on a range of biodiversity indicators and
targets that could be used to develop more effective national
implementation reports and to measure and achieve tangible
progress in implementing the Convention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
