<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Shortage Still Threatens Arab World, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Arab world needs 10 billion
U.S. dollars annually to fill the gap between food production and
consumption, according to a Tunisian official here today.
</P>
<P>
At today's inaugural session of a regional symposium on the
investment and agricultural development, Mohamed Channouchi,
Tunisian Minister of International Cooperation and Investment,
said that food deficiency in the Arab world is expected to
deteriorate in view of the growth of population and scarcity of
water resources.
</P>
<P>
It is anticipated that per capita water supply by the year
2025 will stand at some 667 cubic meters as compared to 3,430
cubic meters in 1960, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for Arab unity to realize the optimum use of human
and natural resources to check the food problem.
</P>
<P>
The Tunisian minister noted the Arab states have intensified
their efforts to develop agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Arab Authority of Investment and Agricultural
Development, founded in 1977 with the object of promoting
agricultural resources in member states, will help improve
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
The organization will do so by specifying investment
opportunities, encouraging partnership and feasibility studies and
finance of increasing numbers of agricultural and food projects,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Youssef Abdul Latif Al Sarkal, chairman of the Arab Authority
of Investment and Agricultural Development, urged the Arab states
to improve economic integration, investment and joint Arab
production capabilities in the agricultural field.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the volume of investment in the
agricultural sector is still humble, not exceeding nine per cent
of the total investments.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition, attended by Tunisia, Morocco, the United Arab
Emirates, Sudan, Syria, Iraq, Mauritania, Saudi Arabia, Qatar,
Kuwait and Jordan, is being held on the sideline of this
symposium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
