<HEADLINE> India Announces New Satellite Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Space Research
Organization (ISRO) today announced a third generation
communication satellite program named "INSAT-3" with five
satellites to be launched over a period of five years from 1999,
the Press Trust of India reported.
</P>
<P>
INSAT-3 will begin with the first launch in 1999 and extend
upto 2003, ISRO Chairman K. Kasturirangan said at a press
conference held in Bangalore, India's Karnataka state.
</P>
<P>
The first two launches would be from abroad, but the consequent
launches could be from India depending on the result of
development in local rockets, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that this third generation satellite would enable the
space agency to build up a communication infrastructure consisting
of 130 transponders by 2005.  
</P>
