<HEADLINE> Envoy to Submit Report on Cyprus to UN Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Resident Representative
Gustave Feissel said here today that he will soon submit a report
on the situation in Cyprus with an assessment of his talks
with the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Feissel made the statement after a meeting with Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides on the preparatory work for direct
negotiations between the two Cypriot sides.
</P>
<P>
He said his report is expected to be submitted in the next few
days prior to Annan's scheduled meeting with Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash in Geneva on April 9. Feissel is expected to
be present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the forthcoming visit to Cyprus of U.N. Chief's
special representative for Cyprus, Han Sung Joo, Feissel said the
purpose of Han's visit is "to have a look at the situation and to
focus on certain things, to give it an extra push to move it
along."
</P>
<P>
According to a U.N. announcement, Han will arrive in Cyprus
on April 12 for a week-long visit, and will then visit
Ankara and Athens for talks on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Han's visit comes amid an ongoing U.N.-sponsored proximity
talks, during which Feissel has held separate bi-weekly meetings
with President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Denktash for
the past three weeks to set the ground for the face-to-face
negotiations between the two community leaders for a solution to
the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Chief Annan has expressed his determination to bring the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides on the island into a direct
negotiation to discuss the solution to the Cyprus problem before
the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the two communities have not met since
October 1994.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of
an Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
