<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Motorways Reopened After Bombs Cleared </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- After clear-up of the bombs, three
motorway routes which were closed Thursday morning after bombing
threats were reopened today with a loss of millions of pounds in
the country's transport industry.
</P>
<P>
The police, after receiving telephoned bomb warnings, went to
the spots immediately Thursday and found two bombs suspected to
have been planted by the IRA (Irish Republican Army).
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people were evacuated from homes and business
places alongside the M1 and M6 routes, and bomb-disposal experts
removed three controlled explosions of suspect packages.
</P>
<P>
The M1 north-south artery reopened Thursday night and the M5
and M6 reopened today, after the police cleared up the area.
</P>
<P>
However, the shutdown of the motorways has affected the
journeys of hundreds of thousands of motorists.
</P>
<P>
Security experts said the IRA had embarked on a pre-election
terror campaign designed to undermine Britain's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Major has condemned the bombing threat and
blamed the IRA for the two bombs that police discovered although
no group has claimed responsibility so far.
</P>
<P>
"It was intended deliberately to cause trouble...It looks as
though it was the IRA playing silly games," Major said Thursday
after the two bombs were found.
</P>
<P>
Last week, two bombs exploded at the important rail junction in
the northwestern town of Wilmslow, and the IRA was blamed for the
incident.
</P>
<P>
The recent bomb threats are likely to heighten the business
community's concern about the economic cost of the deadlock in the
Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
Transport industry officials said the closure of the two major
motorways between the southeast and the industrial northwest has
caused a loss of around 2.3 million pounds (3.7 million
U.S. dollars) an hour to the haulage industry and also snarled up
central England's minor roads with heavy trucks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
