<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turk Arrested for Blaze That Killed His Wife, Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish man was arrested today in
the German city of Krefeld as a suspect of an arson attack that
killed his Turkish wife and two of his children on Monday,
prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
Dieter Menden, spokesman for the prosecutors' office in
Krefeld, said the Turkish man, 42, has not yet been charged. The
Turkish man earlier claimed that he was at a local bar when the
fire broke out in the family's third-floor flat around 2:00
a.m. on Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, investigators found flammable liquid on both sides of
the apartment door leading to the common hallway, suggesting the
attacker had gained access to the apartment. The spokesman could
not immediately disclose details about why the Turk is suspected.
</P>
<P>
The Turk's wife and his 19-year-old daughter died after jumping
out of a third-floor window to escape the fire. His 17-year-old
son remaining in the flat died of smoke inhalation. The
15-year-old twin daughters following her in the jump were
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
The incident has soured ties between Germany and Turkey for
what the Turkish government charged racist motives behind
it. Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan has accused German
authorities of being too lenient with neo-Nazis after arsons in
Germany and the Netherlands that killed nine Turks over the past
seven days.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the Turkish ambassador was summoned to the German
Foreign Ministry to receive a letter from the Bonn government
refuting the charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
