<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Although the full implementation
of the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) will not begin until after the establishment of the SAR on
July 1 this year, the Law has played a very important role in
ensuring the smooth transition of Hong Kong and the establishment
of the SAR, a Chinese official said today.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Guoxiong, deputy director of Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong
 Branch, made the comment at a gathering here today to mark the
seventh anniversary of the promulgation of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to support, after the handover, the SAR
government in its administration and the implementation of the
principle of "one country, two systems", "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong" and a "high degree of autonomy" to ensure
Hong Kong's long-term stability and prosperity, Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of the
Hong Kong SAR, said the Basic Law is the guideline for the
policies and provisions to be worked out by the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law has laid down the principles of "one country, two
 systems", "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and a "high
degree of autonomy" in legal form. It also provides the political
framework concerning the relationship between the SAR and the
central government, and all other aspects of Hong Kong's social
life, he continued.
</P>
<P>
With just 88 days left before the handover, the preparatory
work for the establishment of the SAR government is in procession
on due schedule, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm fully confident of Hong Kong's future," the SAR Chief
Executive added.
</P>
<P>
Among other speakers were Wang Fengchao, deputy chief of the
Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office under the State Council, Gu
Yongjiang, chairman of the Hong Kong Chinese Enterprises
Association, Major General Xiong Ziren, political commissar of the
 People's Liberation Army (PLA) Garrison in Hong Kong, and Rita
Fan, president of the Provisional legislature of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Wang gave a detailed explanation on issues of the nationality
and the right of abode of Hong Kong people, which has attracted
attention from various quarters.
</P>
<P>
Gu stated his views on the prospects of the Hong Kong economy
and the development of the Chinese-invested enterprises in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Xiong said that the PLA garrison will be mainly responsible for
the defense of the HKSAR and, when needed, will assist the SAR
government in maintaining law and order and provide disaster
relief.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the PLA garrison shall act as ordinary members
of the Hong Kong society and abide by the HKSAR laws as well as
military disciplines.
</P>
<P>
In her speech, Rita Fan said that the election of a Hong Kong
resident as head of the HKSAR is a democratic procedure made
possible by the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the Provisional Legislature is the only
way to avoid a legal vacuum after the British side implemented its
"reform package," thus derailing the through-train mechanism of
the current Legislative Council. It is also consistent with the
principle of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Legislature needs to start work before July 1,
1997 as there is a lot of preparatory work to be done. The
Provisional Legislature will be dissolved upon the formation of
the first Legislative Council of the HKSAR at a date no later than
June 30, 1998, she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
