<HEADLINE> U.N., EU Call for Aid Access to Refugees in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations (U.N.) and the
European Union (EU) today called for free access for humanitarian
aid for the refugees in Zaire as Zairean parties gathered in South
Africa to begin negotiations to bring peace to the country.
</P>
<P>
"We appeal to the participants in the talks to fully consider
the urgent humanitarian needs of hundreds of thousands of refugees
and displaced Zaireans stranded in the war zone," said a joint
statement by leaders of U.N. and EU aid agencies.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of the Zairean government led by President Mobutu
Sese Seko today arrived at Pretoria, South Africa, for
U.N.-brokered peace talks on this weekend with the rebel force,
the Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of
Congo-Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, vowing to bring Seko down from power, has
controlled a quarter of the country's territory after six months
of fighting with government troops.
</P>
<P>
The officials called on the parties to respect humanitarian
principles and allow relief workers and supplies free access to
refugees.
</P>
<P>
"Aid agencies should be able to work without any restrictions
to save many thousands of refugees and displaced persons... whose
lives are currently hanging by a thread," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Over the past week, the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR), the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), the
World Food Program (WFP) and other aid agencies have been trying
to send food and other life necessities to more than 100,000
refugees who have re-emerged from the forest.
</P>
<P>
However, many Rwandan and Burundi refugees and displaced
Zaireans were still out of reach.
</P>
<P>
The agencies also urged the international community to help
with aid delivery and the repatriation of those who wish to return
home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
