<HEADLINE> Singapore Offers Commitment to UN Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Singapore has given its
commitment to putting the Singapore Armed Forces (SAF) and police
personnel on standby to take part in the United Nations
peacekeeping mission at short notice, Deputy Prime Minister Tony
Tan said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a send-off ceremony for the seventh team of
military observers to the U.N. Iraq-Kuwait Observer Mission, Tony
Tan, who is also defense minister, said Singapore was negotiating
a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) with the U.N. to formalize its
commitment to the UN Standby Arrangements.
</P>
<P>
It was understood that this would include planning officers,
military observers, medical personnel, and transport aircraft and
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Tony Tan said Singapore's participation in the peacekeeping
missions was constrained by the country's manpower resources.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that Singapore had and would continue to take
part in missions where it could make a valuable and effective
contribution to the maintenance of peace and stability.  
</P>
