<HEADLINE> French Government Rejects British Bidding for Thomson CSF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The French government today rejected
a bidding by the British company GEC-Marconi for buying its
majority stake in the electronics-defense company Thomson CSF,
saying it would harm France's national security.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Economy and Finance said in a communique that
two French groups, the merger of Alcatel Asthom and Dassault
Industrie, and the Lagardere Media-Defense Group, are acceptable
as the bidders for Thomson CSF.
</P>
<P>
"The transfer of more than 50 percent of the capital of Thomson
CSF (to a foreign company) is contrary to the essential interests
of the national security," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The French government, expected to announce on April 7 which
bidder for the company complies with its conditions for the sale,
said that it encourages all the candidates to tell which French or
European companies they would like to be their partners in the
take-over.
</P>
<P>
It also said Paris hopes the privatization of Thomson CSF would
bring about the restructuring of the company, which failed to make
any profits for years until 1996, when it earned a net profit of
745 million francs (135 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government refused to confirm until today the candidacy by
GEC-Marconi, as that would be a highly sensitive issue considering
the high defense technology owned by Thomson CSF.
</P>
<P>
The French government intends to build Thomson CSF into one of
the world's largest defense groups allying numerous European
companies to compete with U.S. defense companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
