<HEADLINE> U.S. Sailor Questioned in Sex Assault in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese police questioned a
U.S. Navy sailor Wednesday on suspicion of assaulting and
molesting a young Japanese woman at the Yokosuka naval base in
Kanagawa Prefecture, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese police, assuming full jurisdiction in the case,
questioned the detained 26-year-old petty officer third class with
the assistance of the U.S. Navy criminal investigators, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The sailor, who was assigned to a naval computer and
telecommunications station at the base, was taken into custody
Wednesday by the U.S. Navy authorities after the base security
forces responded to a report on a disturbance at the servicemen's
barracks, where they found a 21-year-old local woman.
</P>
<P>
The woman said that she had been sexually assaulted and taken
to a local hospital afterwards where she was treated for "a broken
clavicle, abrasions and contusions," the U.S. Navy officials was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred on the eve of U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen's first official visit to Japan next week. Observers
said it could intensify the bitter dispute between the United
States and Japan over U.S. military bases in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The September 1995 rape of an Okinawa schoolgirl by three
U.S. servicemen has spurred a strong opposition in the prefecture
to the U.S. military presence in Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
