<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Basic Law Warrants "One Country, Two Systems", HK Newspapers Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Basic Law provides a legal
guarantee for materializing the principles of "one country, two
systems" and "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and for
maintaining the territory's long-term stability and prosperity,
Hong Kong newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po, Ta Kung Pao, and some other major local newspapers
today rolled out editorials, commentaries and signed articles to
mark the seventh anniversary of the promulgation of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial entitled "One country, Two Systems Soon to
become Reality", Wen Wei Po said that the Basic Law warrants
"one country, two systems" in a concrete and legal form, and
provides a strong guarantee for Hong Kong's prosperity and
stability.
</P>
<P>
The promulgation of the Basic Law coincided with Hong Kong's
entry into the later years of the transition period. During the
crucial years, Britain changed its Hong Kong policy, making
troubles and obstacles in the way of the smooth transition, said
the paper.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese government and Hong Kong people have been
adhering firmly to the Basic Law, and Britain's plans to stir up
chaos were foiled, the paper said. The situation in Hong Kong is
now becoming ever encouraging.
</P>
<P>
A lot of preparations for the formation of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) have been completed, and
now the Chief Executive-elect, the Provisional Legislative
Council and the Executive Council are carrying out their work in
an orderly and highly effective way, it said.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after Hong Kong's return to the motherland, the
HKSAR will operate smoothly in accordance with the Basic Law, the
paper concluded.
</P>
<P>
Ta Kung Pao's editorial pointed out that the Basic Law, which
turns the principle of "one country, two systems" into specific
clauses, illustrates the wisdom and efforts of the
people in both Hong Kong and the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that with its implementation after Hong Kong's
return, the law will become more influential.
</P>
<P>
An editorial in the Hong Kong Commercial Daily called the Basic
Law a "magic pearl" calming down stormy waves in the sea and a
"lighthouse" guiding Hong Kong people through the transition
period.
</P>
<P>
In spite of all the trials and hardships, thanks to the Basic
Law, Hong Kong people have always been confident about the
territory's future and foreign investors also see good prospects
for Hong Kong, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past seven years, the Basic Law has been deeply rooted
in the minds and hearts of Hong Kong people, and it has been an
unswerving consensus of Hong Kong people to support, implement and
uphold the law, it said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Economic Times said in an editorial that the whole
process of working out the law -- drafting, advice-seeking,
revision and promulgation -- stretched as long as five years, and
that it has won the backing of Hong Kong people and the respect of
the international community.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
