<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Movie About Tibetans Well Received </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese movie which depicts
Tibetans and Hans and their show of patriotism when fighting
against British invaders in the late 19th century has received
public acclaim.
</P>
<P>
Film circles consider "Red River Valley", produced by the
Shanghai Film Studio at a cost of 15 million yuan, the best of the
films that reflect the Tibetan life. And China's film critics are
saying the movie can compete with imported foreign films on the
market.
</P>
<P>
The drama takes place 100 years ago in Tibet, focusing on a
group of British explorers in the region who were treated kindly
by local people. However, both the Hans and Tibetans united to
defend their homeland against British colonists hoping to claim
the exotic area as their own.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the film, Jose, a war reporter in the British
army, kneels on a snow-covered mountain and asks, "Why do we try
to use our world to change their world? This is a nationality
which will never give in or disappear, behind which is the East, a
piece of land we can never conquer!"
</P>
<P>
Award-winning director Feng Xiaoning said: "Invasions can only
bring disasters or destroy. Equality, kindness and friendship are
bridges between different nationalities and cultures."
</P>
<P>
Feng said the movie's theme is patriotism, adding that
"patriotism is very important to a nation whenever it is in danger
or stepping toward prosperity."
</P>
<P>
Movie-goers will get a hefty dose of Tibet's blue skies, clear
rivers and snow-capped plateau, and also be exposed to the unique
customs of the Tibetan people.
</P>
<P>
Feng and his production company set a world record by shooting
on a mountain 6,000 meters above sea level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
