<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Says Labor's Manifesto "Flaky" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
today criticized the opposition Labor Party's manifesto,
describing its spending plans as "flaky."
</P>
<P>
"Tony (Blair) hasn't yet to face any of the difficult
decisions. When he is tackled on detail and policy, it seems to me
they are rather flaky," Major told local media.
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Tony Blair Thursday unveiled his policy blueprint
for the May 1 general election, offering a "10-commitment covenant
with the people" in which he pledged no increase of income tax
rates.
</P>
<P>
In the manifesto, Blair also promised to give top priority to
education and provide job opportunities for about 250,000 young
unemployed people if he wins the election.
</P>
<P>
However, Major said the Labor's pledge had a gap of at least
1.5 billion pounds (2.46 billion U.S. dollars) between its tax and
spending plans.
</P>
<P>
Major's Conservative Party has been ruling the country for the
past 18 years since Margaret Thatcher took power in 1979. Despite
the fact that the Conservatives were now trailing the Labor by up
to 24 points in the latest opinion polls, Major said he was still
confident in the upcoming election, adding he would win victory as
he did in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In the previous election, the opinion polls showed the
Conservatives were lagging behind the Labor, while the voting
turned out that Major's Conservative Party led the Labor by 21
seats in the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
