<HEADLINE> China, Indonesia Pledge to Strengthen Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China and Indonesia today pledged
to strengthen their bilateral relations which have developed
satisfactorily since the restoration of diplomatic ties between
the two countries six years ago.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made by Indonesian President Soeharto and
visiting Chinese State Councilor and Secretary-General of the
State Council Luo Gan during their meeting at the Merdeka Place
here.
</P>
<P>
Both sides held that the consolidation and development of the
relations is not only beneficial to the peoples of the two
countries, but is also helpful to peace, stability and prosperity
in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto said Indonesia and China should expand their economic
and trade relations, especially the exchange of technology and
culture.
</P>
<P>
Luo Gan spoke highly of Indonesia's policy on developing
Indonesian-China relations.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government is satisfied with the
good-neighborly relations based on the five principles of peaceful
coexistence and the principles of the Bandung (Asia-Africa)
Conference.
</P>
<P>
China is ready to make common efforts with Indonesia to push
their 21st century-oriented relations towards a new stage, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Luo arrived in Indonesia's tourist island of Bali on Tuesday
and in the capital of Jakarta on Thursday for a six-day visit at
the invitation of Sinister/State Secretary Moerdiono.
</P>
<P>
He also met with Vice President Try Sutrisno, acting foreign
minister Edi Sudrajat and Moerdiono this morning.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono told Luo that Indonesia will always stick to its "one
China" policy and will continue to support China on the human
rights issue.
</P>
<P>
Luo and his party will leave here on Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
