<HEADLINE> China's First Buddhist Charity Fund Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The two-year-old South Putuo Temple
Charity Fund, the first of its kind on the Chinese mainland, has
been widely praised for its generous and timely donations to poor
people and victims of natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The Provincial Bureau of Religious Affairs of Fujian Province
recently presented fund organizers with an inscribed bronze plate
in recognition for work done by the charity, which was set up in
Xiamen, in Fujian Province, on December 14, 1994.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, the fund donated over 1.8 million yuan
to disaster victims, orphans and other needy people. It has also
offered 460,000 yuan to the Hope Project, a national charity for
helping students in the poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The fund's charity hospital, which was set up in December 1995,
has treated over 70,000 patients gratis and distributed, free of
charge, medicine valued at over 200,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city's Social Welfare Center, home of 80
orphans, has received funding and electric appliances including
washing machines, tape-recorders, color TVs, water-heaters and
gas-ovens, as donations of the charity fund.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
