<HEADLINE> Banned Referee Appeal to Heard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Former referee Kurt Rothlisberger's
 appeal against a life ban for attempting to fix a European
Champions League match will be heard by the European football
Union on April 10.
</P>
<P>
According to UEFA, Rothlisberger tried to fix the 1996 tie
between French first division side Auxerre and Swiss champions
Grasshopper Zurich, a report from AFP said today.
</P>
<P>
UEFA claim Rothlisberger contacted Grasshopper officials two
weeks before the match, saying he was a friend of the Belarus
referee in charge of the match and that if they wanted he could
fix the result.
</P>
<P>
Rothlisberger, one of the world's best known referees and
veteran of more than 1,000 matches, is reported to have demanded
over 60,000 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
