<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank on Ties between Shanghai, Hong Kong as Financial Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior bank official said that
Shanghai's bid to become a regional financial center will not
undermine Hong Kong's position as an international financial hub
after its return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Mao Yingliang, director of the Shanghai branch of the People's
Bank of China, said Hong Kong will be able to develop itself into
a leading international financial center like New York and London,
backed by China's booming economy and vast market in general.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the country's sizable economy can
support two financial centers at the same time, and Shanghai's
drive, instead of challenging Hong Kong's status quo, will only
help propel the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region forward.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will benefit a lot from such a partnership with
Shanghai, particularly in furthering involvement in mainland
projects," Mao said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Shanghai, being the country's largest trade and
financial city, will become a stepping-stone for Hong Kong to
further increase its investment in the inland parts of China after
its return on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Mao said that Shanghai is qualified to help Hong Kong investors
deal with businesses in the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
China will continue its strong demand for more overseas
investment for a long time to come, and this will generate more
business opportunities for Hong Kong investors, who have always
been one of the most important sources of overseas investment over
the past years.
</P>
<P>
There is also a great potential to be tapped between Hong Kong
and Shanghai, which can function as an outlet of cash outflows
from Hong Kong, and help Hong Kong investors to understand the
fiscal laws and administration on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
"The wholesale capital from Hong Kong can flow into the inland
market via Shanghai, since the city has become a nationwide market
of many investment instruments, such as foreign exchange,
inter-bank loans, and securities," Mao noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
