<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Establish Unified Treasury Bond System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Besides developing the over-the-counter government bond market,
China this year will gradually establish a united national bond
registration, custody, settlement, and clearance system, Gao Jian,
director of the ministry's State Debt Mangement Department, said
at an international seminar on social guarantee funds management,
which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
"At present, treasury bond clearance, settlement, and custody
are carried out in the respective exchanges while the transfer of
custody of government bonds is simply impossible, which is
detrimental to the development of the bond market," Gao said,
</P>
<P>
The director said that also this year the process of making
government bonds paperless will be accelerated and the
non-mobility of paper bonds will be realized.
</P>
<P>
To help further improve the central bank's ability to regulate
the money supply and implement its monetary policy more
effectively, the MOF will continue to issue short-term treasury
bonds, maintaining a relatively fixed timetable, Gao said.
</P>
<P>
Medium-term bonds should be floated when old bonds are
redeemed, in order to stabilize the market, he said.
</P>
<P>
China resumed the practice of issuing treasury bonds in 1981
and its annual issue expanded rapidly in recent years, hitting a
record 196 billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, China had issued over 660 billion
yuan-worth of government bonds, with the outstanding volume
standing at 440 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's treasury bond issue this year is budgeted at 248.596
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The three-day seminar was co-sponsored by the Ministry of
Finance and Lincoln National Corporation of the United States and
attended by officials and experts from China, the United States,
the World Bank, Chile, Singapore, Canada and some countries in
East Europe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
