<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Steps Up Efforts to Eliminate TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is stepping up its
efforts to eliminate tuberculosis (TB) in the country, and it
launched a comprehensive program today with an aim to rid the
republic of the disease in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The program, called the Singapore Tuberculosis Elimination
Program, or STEP, is said to be the only such national program in
the world currently.
</P>
<P>
Launching the program, Health Minister Yeo Cheow Tong said that
such a program was necessary because there are some 1,500 new
cases of TB every year in the country, although prevention methods
are available.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, the incidence of TB has not declined since
1987, the minister said, noting that in Singapore, the rate of TB
in the population stood at 55 per 100,000, comparing poorly with
the rates in the developed countries which range between five and
10 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
Yeo said the program's priority is to detect all infectious TB
cases through systematic screening of high risk persons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
