<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Bank Chief Calls for Higher Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Bank of England Governor Eddie
George said Thursday that he would press any new government after
the general election for higher interest rates to slow the upswing
and guard against inflation, local press reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the annual meeting of the Foreign Bankers'
Association in Amsterdam, the British central bank head admitted
that a rise in interest rates would hurt British exporters with
the pound so strong, but argued that the decision had to be made
in the light of economic conditions generally, not just the
situation faced by exporters.
</P>
<P>
"You cannot reasonably expose the economy as a whole to
inflationary risks in order to protect the tradeable sectors," he
added.
</P>
<P>
His view was hardened by the results of two separate surveys.
</P>
<P>
The latest distributive trades survey of the Confederation of
British Industry (CBI) confirmed Thursday that a positive balance
of 33 percent of retailers enjoyed sales growth in March, compared
with 24 percent in February and 27 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of retailers expecting sales to improve
in April also rose to 40 percent from 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
Another survey, The Report on Service, the first of its kind
relies on evidence from 500 companies involved in a wide range of
service sector activities, also revealed buoyant conditions across
the sector and suggested that the pace of activity was
accelerating.
</P>
<P>
The survey, published Thursday by the Chartered Institute of
Purchasing and Supply, provided a warning about inflationary
pressures building up in the economy.
</P>
<P>
It said prices charged by purchasing managers had risen for the
fifth consecutive month and further pressure on prices was
expected because of a significant increase in service sector
wages, particularly among the highly skilled.
</P>
<P>
However, Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke has stood
firm for several months against pressures for higher interest
rates, arguing that the strength of the pound is hurting
manufacturing industry and has proved a powerful deflationary
force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
