<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Energy Source for Rural Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Rural northern China has been
successful in developing clean energy by constructing
methane-generating pits in courtyards of farmers' homes.
</P>
<P>
This not only has helped boost rural economy but also has
effectively protected the environment, according to
a two-day meeting on experiments with energy development in
rural northern China, which ended today here in Dalian, an
open port city of northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
With the colder climate in northern China, many rural areas
have started a comprehensive project that cover a vegetable
greenhouse, a methane-generating pit, a pig pen, and a toilet in
the courtyard of a rural home.
</P>
<P>
The model has been introduced in provinces of Liaoning, Jilin,
Shanxi, Shandong, Shaanxi, Qinghai, Hebei, Henan and Inner
Mongolia and Ningxia Hui autonomous regions, and good economic,
social, and ecological benefits have been reported.
</P>
<P>
Hong Fuzeng, Chinese vice-minister of agriculture, said the
model has closely connected breeding and plantation and formed a
complete production cycling system.
</P>
<P>
Hong praised the model as an effective way to boost farm
production in poor areas to help get rid of poverty.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister disclosed that his ministry would encourage
to spread this important model in 1997, the year for popularizing
of agro-techniques in China.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this century, this rural energy development model
will have been spread among 30 to 40 percent of rural households
of 18 provinces and autonomous regions in northern China, the
vice-ministry said, adding that it would be a great but arduous
task.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Province of northeast China had over 110,000 rural
households that had tried the method of developing courtyard
economy by building small methane-generating pits by 1996.
</P>
<P>
Sample surveys show that average rural household income of the
province can reach 5,000 yuan a year, accounting for 50 percent of
a household's entire income.
</P>
<P>
Through energy construction in rural areas, Liaoning has formed
a capacity of developing and saving energy equivalent to 3.19
million tons of standard coal, and is able to supply the market
with 100 million kg of pollution-free vegetables and provide 1.12
million live hogs a year.
</P>
<P>
Yang Shiji, a research worker with the Rural Economic Institute
of the Chinese Academy of Agricultural Sciences, hailed the
comprehensive energy development method as a "breakthrough," as
the method can help save crop stalks from burning and can help
increase the fertility of the soil by returning the stalks back to
the fields and eventually improve the reserve strength of
agricultural production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
