<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao External Trade Recovering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Both Macao's imports and exports
recorded an increase for the first time in a year in January, the
latest statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Figures released today by the Macao Census and Statistics
Department show that the export value reached 1.6 billion patacas
(about 202.5 million US dollars) in January, up 37.6 percent from
the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The value of import topped 1.3 billion patacas (about 164.6
million US dollars), an increase of 10.9 percent from a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a trade surplus was scored for the first time
after running a deficit for the whole of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Among the total exports, 86 percent were textile and garment
products, whose volume rose 52.9 percent, while the export of
non-textile products, including machinery and instruments,
footwear and cement products, dropped 14.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of Macao's exports went to the United States
and the European Union nations. Sales to both places increased by
over 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Macao imported more goods from the Asian-Pacific region,
including China's mainland, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Japan and
Australia. The imports from South Korea, however, sank by 17
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
