<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Burkina Faso Seek Closer African Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- African nations have been asked to
initiate measures at national, regional and continental levels to
ensure effective economic integration of member countries of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Sani Abacha and President
Blaise Compaore of Burkina Faso made the call at the end of a
two-day visit to Nigeria by the Burkinabe leader, according to
press reports today.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued in Abuja, capital of Nigeria, on
Thursday, the two leaders reaffirmed the need to strengthen the
various cooperation agreements between both countries through
regular and sustained contacts as well as consultations at all
levels of government.
</P>
<P>
According to the leaders, such contacts are building blocks
for effective regional and continental economic integration of
member countries and OAU and others like the Economic Community
of West African States.
</P>
<P>
They stated that "effective bilateral and regional cooperation
among the brotherly countries of the sub-region are necessary
prerequisites for regional economic integration," to which the
two countries are fully committed.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders expressed concern at the recent escalation of
crisis in the Horn of Africa, calling on African states to seek
solutions to their problems through process and mechanisms
existing within the continent.
</P>
<P>
To this end, they acknowledged the roles played by countries
in the sub-region in search for peace in Liberia particularly
where progress is being made in the implementation of the latest
Abuja peace agreement of August 1996.
</P>
<P>
They also called for an immediate ceasefire and negotiations
between the government of Zaire and the leader of the
Democratic Alliance for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire Laurent
Desire Kabila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
