<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, New Zealand Agree on Air Traffic Arrangements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and New Zealand have
recently reached an agreement over new air traffic arrangements
that provide for a balanced exchange of traffic rights for the
airlines of both places, an official release said here today.
</P>
<P>
Flexible and expansionary, the new arrangements reflect the
needs of the market and open up opportunities for growth in
tourism, a spokesman for the Hong Kong Economic Services Branch
said.
</P>
<P>
The new arrangements offer travelers a chance to stop in
Australia on their trips from Hong Kong to New Zealand, and vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
The business traveler will also stand to benefit. Hong
Kong-based Cathay Pacific, for instance, currently operates only
five non-stop services per week between Hong Kong and Auckland.
Under the new arrangements, however, the company could plan to
gradually increase this to a daily flight by early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific, together with Air New Zealand, carried a total
of 200,000 passengers in 1996, an increase of 23 percent over
1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hong Kong Tourist Association, 32,900 Hong
Kong residents visited New Zealand in 1996, up 12 percent over
1995, while 58,000 New Zealand residents visited the territory in
1996, up 16 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The new arrangements were negotiated under the umbrella of the
Hong Kong/New Zealand Air Services Agreement signed in February
1991, with the talks stretching over four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
