<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Economy Expected to Get Extra Impulse from EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch economy will get an
extra impulse for growth in 1998 if the European Economic and
Monetary Union (EMU) proceeds without significant problems, a
senior Dutch official said today.
</P>
<P>
However, if the EMU is in danger, economic growth in the
Netherlands will fall below the estimate by the Central Planning
Bureau (CPB) in its Central Economic Plan (CEP) published on
Thursday, said Henk Don, CPB director of the Netherlands, to the
newspaper Het Financieele Dagblad.
</P>
<P>
"The formation of EMU is a major uncertainty in our economy, in
both the positive and negative sense," he added.
</P>
<P>
Don added that a smooth transition to EMU on January 1, 1999,
is a guarantee for further strengthening of both consumer and
producer confidence in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"But if EMU fails to take place then, the economy will lose its
force," he warned.
</P>
<P>
According to the CEP, the Dutch gross domestic product for this
year and 1988 is projected to grow at 3 percent and 3.25 percent
respectively, higher than in any other countries in the European
Union whose average growth is between 2.3-2.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
