<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Transport Services to be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The South African Transport
Department has started a program to commercialize and privatize
all its services around the country, local daily "The Star"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The program will include all modes of transport and will be
completed over a period of four to seven years, Director-General
Ketso Gordhan of the Transport Department was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the long-term plan, airlines, ports and railways around
the country will be operated independently. This will include the
possibility that South African Airways will be privatized, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the government's decision to loosen its grip on
transportation, Gordhan said this has become necessary because of
the changing role of the government.
</P>
<P>
The South African government is reportedly the biggest
transport operator in the country, responsible for between 70 and
80 percent of all transport.
</P>
<P>
Local informed sources said the transport reform will possibly
bring about a reduction in the Transport Department's staff from
1,053 to 270.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a series of agencies will be set up and run by the
private sector. Each will employ its own staff, who will not be
public servants and have chief executive officers to run them,
the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
