<HEADLINE> Britain's Prince Andrew to Visit Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Prince Andrew, the duke
of York, is scheduled to visit Zimbabwe from April 15 to 17 and
attend the first multi-national peacekeeping exercise involving
troops from central and southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The British royal is visiting Zimbabwe at the personal
invitation of Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, who extended
the invitation during his recent visit to London.
</P>
<P>
The multi-national peacekeeping exercise, also called Exercise
Blue Hungwe, is organized with the assistance of Britain and is
running from April 4 to 20 at the Zimbabwe national army training
base in Nyanga, northeast of the country.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,100 troops from Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Namibia,
South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania and Zimbabwe, all of whom are
members of the commonwealth, are participating in the exercise.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the British High Commission said on Thursday,
"the aim of exercise is to enhance regional African liaison,
cooperation and military skills by means of multi-national joint
field training exercise based on the UN tactics and techniques of
international peacekeeping." 
</P>
</TEXT>
