<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's National Economy on Steady, Healthy Growth in 1996 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China's national economy
registered a moderately fast growth in 1996, with inflation under
control, and the overheated economy slowed to a normal growth
rate, said the Statistical Communique on the 1996 National
Economics and Social Development released by State Statistical
Bureau (SSB) today.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary statistics indicated that the gross domestic
product of China in 1996 was 6,779.5 billion yuan, a real growth
of 9.7 percent over the previous year. Though somewhat slower as
compared with the growth rate during earlier years, the current
economic growth still fell into the range of high growth, and was
in conformity with the availability of resources and demands of
the market.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the same months in 1995, the momentum of increase
of market retail prices slowed down month by month in 1996. The
annual increase in the price index was 6.1 percent, well below the
control target of the central government.
</P>
<P>
It is preliminarily estimated that the aggregate supply of the
society in 1996 was 8,021.2 billion yuan while the aggregate
demand was 8,350.1 billion yuan, with a gap of 328.9 billion, or a
balance rate of -4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's agriculture sector generated a sharp increase of
1,355 billion yuan in its added value, up by 5.1 percent over
1995, while the grain output hit a historical high, reaching 490
million tons.
</P>
<P>
The industrial production kept steady growth in a country-wide
enterprise adjustment. In 1996, the total value-added of the
industrial sector was 2,858 billion yuan, up by 12.7 percent over
the previous year. Meanwhile, the service industry created an
added value of 2,109.7 billion yuan, a rise of eight percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's National Economy on Steady, Healthy Growth in 1996 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the communique, the completed investment in fixed
assets of the country stood at 2,366 billion yuan last year,
representing a real increase margin of 12.7 percent over that of
1995, if price increase is excluded.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, steady growth was found in foreign investment, 55.27
billion US dollars in 1996, up 14.2 percent over the previous
year. Of this total, 42.35 billion dollars was in the form of
foreign direct investment, a yearly increase of 12.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year saw the country further expand its foreign trade
scale, with the total volume of export and import reached 289.9
billion US dollars, up 3.2 percent over the 1995 figure. The trade
surplus continued in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Further improvement was also made in the livelihood of the
Chinese people. The annual per-capita income of urban households
was 4,377 yuan last year, up 12.4 percent over 1995, or a real
growth of 3.3 percent if price hikes was excluded. The per capita
net income of rural households was 1,926 yuan, up 22 percent, and
the real growth stood at nine percent at the 1995 prices.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here today, Zhang Sai, director
of SSB, said that such a "healthy development" of the economy in
1996 signals a good start for the country's ambitious Ninth
Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
Thus, the national economy will continue to grow in a stable
and harmonious manner throughout the year 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
In explaining the statistical methods for the communique, the
director said that the SSB has established statistical indicator
systems which are based on the strict data processing technologies
and the well-organized sampling mechanism. In case there is any
figure exaggerated or deliberately reduced by local governments,
the state-level statistical body is able to make corrections in
time, so as to safeguard the bureau's correctness and authority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Agrees On Curbing Trade Surplus With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 4 (Xinhua) - Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto and visiting U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin today
agreed to prevent Japan's trade surplus with the United States
from growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in Tokyo, Hashimoto told Rubin that Japan's
current account surplus will not expand dramatically, Kyodo News
Service reported.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting, Rubin and Japanese Finance Minister
Hiroshi Mitsuzuka also reached a similar understanding, Kyodo
quoted government officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The United States has expressed concern that Japan's trade
surplus may show an uptrend again due to rising exports as the yen
remains weak against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Rubin visited Japan en route to Cebu Island in the Philippines
to attend a meeting of finance ministers from the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation forum slated for Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
