<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Being Used in Bird Smuggling, Says WWF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Highly lucrative international
smuggling rings dealing in endangered birds and native animals
species are using New Zealand in bird smuggling, the World Wide
Fund for Nature said today.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Press Association quoted Chris Laidlaw,
executive director of WWF in New Zealand, as saying that the trade
in endangered species was huge.
</P>
<P>
Laidlaw said New Zealand was being used as an international
staging post where eggs were illegally smuggled in, and hatched
into birds which were then used to produce legal offspring for the
international export market.
</P>
<P>
It was the bird equivalent of international money laundering,
he charged.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very, very lively trade at work. There are birds
coming in and out of Australia and New Zealand."
</P>
<P>
"The trade involves mainly Australian birds, mainly parrots but
it also involves a variety of New Zealand species as well,"
Laidlaw said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
