<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Petroleum Hamdy Banby announced
Thursday a new natural gas find in the Mediterranean Sea North
Rosetta city.
</P>
<P>
The find lies at a depth of 1490 meters and one stratum has
been tested and found to be giving off natural gas at the rate of
300 million cubic feet per day, the local daily Al-Akhbar
reported today.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- ANZ Banking Group Lt., one of Australia's four
largest banks, opened a branch in East Jerusalem this week,
reported The Jerusalem Post Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which has some 100 billion U.S. dollars in assets
throughout 43 mostly Asian countries, said it will focus on
winning corporate and institutional business across the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
Israeli bankers hope the Australian bank will help speed up
cooperation between Israel and the leading Asian financial
centers, given ANZ's interests in China, Japan, South Korea,
Vietnam, the Philippines, Indonesia and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli state income in the first quarter of
1997 totaled 26.8 billion shekels (about 8.4 billion US dollars),
a 4.7 percent increase in real terms compared with the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury said the figures are a key factor in deciding
whether to implement a second budget cut in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli parliament, Knesset, approved a 7.2 billion shekel
budget cut on December 31 to restrict the country's annual
deficit to the government-set target of 2.8 percent of gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Occupancy in hotels in Jerusalem and Tel Aviv is
expected to drop by about 25 percent during Pessah, a Jewish
festival from April 22 to 28, as a result of cancellations by
tourists from abroad, reported the Jerusalem Post Friday.
</P>
<P>
Pnina Elazar, a spokesperson for the Israel Hotel Association,
said the cancellations came from both individuals and groups who
had planned to spend the holiday in Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The cancellations are also coming in for the long range. They
see that the tension is not a short-term affair," said Yonatan
Harpaz, director of the Jerusalem Hotel Association.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The World Bank agreed to offer several grants of 262
million US dollars to Egypt to finance some projects in the North
African country.
</P>
<P>
According to Khaled Ikram, the World Bank's resident
representative in Egypt, 75 million dollars of the grants will be
allocated for education, 50 million dollars for health, 17 million
dollars for housing and 120 million dollars for the Social Fund
for Development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
