<HEADLINE> Dutch Civil Servants to Get Wage Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands' 106,000 civil
servants are to receive a 2.8 percent structural pay rise from
May 1 this year, followed by a 2.4 percent hike on July 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the local reports today, the pay-and-condition
(CAO) pact was agreed Wednesday by Vice Prime Minister and
Interior Minister Hans Dijkstal and the trade unions.
</P>
<P>
In addition, government employees' year-end bonus will be
topped up by 0.5 percent of their gross annual salaries. State
employees will also be able to cash in three to four holiday days
each year under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The CAO is more expensive than Dijkstal had expected. "I have
mixed feelings about the financial consequences of the deal. It's
higher than I had wanted and it goes a bit further than we
possibly should have done."
</P>
<P>
Dijkstal now has to negotiate new CAOs for the country's
190,000 municipal employees, 8,000 water board workers and 40,000
police officers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
