<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wang Fengchao on Nationality, Right of Abode of HK People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official talked
about some principles concerning the nationality and the right of
abode of Hong Kong residents in connection with the provisions of
the Basic Law here today at a seminar marking the 7th anniversary
of the promulgation of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Wang Fengchao, Deputy Chief of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs
Office under the Chinese State Council, said that the Chinese
Nationality Law will go into effect in Hong Kong beginning from
July 1, 1997. The Law shall determine who among Hong Kong
residents will be Chinese citizens and who will not be.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a major manifestation of the resumption of the
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong by the Chinese Government
and will also be the power due to a sovereign country," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, the requirements for acquiring the
identity of permanent residents in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) will be based on the Chinese
Nationality Law, he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained to participants of the seminar the efforts the
Chinese Government has made in this respect and some specific
solutions to issues that might crop up in the implementation of
the relevant provisions of the Basic Law concerning the Right of
Abode.
</P>
<P>
He said that due to both legal and historical reasons, the
question of nationality and the right of abode of Hong Kong people
is a fairly complicated one.
</P>
<P>
"In the past seven years since the Basic Law was adopted, the
Chinese Government has consistently attached great importance to
this question and stressed time and again that in handling
relevant questions in this connection, it is necessary to respect
history and respect the reality, and settle them in a liberal,
flexible and practical way," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Now there are only 88 days left before the Basic Law goes into
effect. I believe, when that day comes, the HKSAR will provide
perfect legal guarantee on the question of the nationality and the
right of abode of the Hong Kong people," he stated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
