<HEADLINE> Vietnam Plans to Increase Steel Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam plans to bring its total
steel production up to 2-2.2 million tons by the year 2000 and
7-7.5 million tons by 2010 to meet the increasing domestic demand,
Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The demand for steel in Vietnam is estimated to rise 20 percent
annually to the year 2000 and 14-15 percent in the following ten
years.
</P>
<P>
All the existing steel factories, even at full capacity, can
only meet 60 percent of the requirements, the VNA said.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial Ministry planned to concentrate on intensive
investment to raise production and reduce costs and give priority
to foreign investment in producing billets, sheet steel and other
steel products to substitute imports.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for production of one million tons of steel
billets a year up to 2000 and import of about 2.1 million tons of
other kinds of steel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
