<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monetary Situation Stable in Philippines: Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson said today that the monetary and price situation
in the Philippines continues to be generally stable.
</P>
<P>
In a report submitted to President Fidel Ramos, Singson said
that based on the auction conducted on March 24, the interest
rates of treasury bills for all tenors dropped for the fifth
consecutive week.
</P>
<P>
The auction, he said, was marked by over-subscription in all
tenors as average yields for all maturities dropped by 12.7 basis
points to settle at 10.158 percent from the previous week's 10.285
percent.
</P>
<P>
The bellwether 91-day T-bill rate remained at a single digit
level settling at 9.724 percent, lower by 8 basis points than the
previous week's, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
Compared to the 90-day London Interbank Offered Rate (LIBOR) of
5.62 percent for March 17-21, the gap between the 91-day T-bill
rate and LIBOR narrowed further to 4.104 percentage points from
the previous week's 4.244 percentage points, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
He said the 182-day and 364-day T-bill yields, meanwhile,
contracted further by 16.5 basis points and 12.1 basis points,
respectively, to reach 9.969 percent and 10.517 percent from the
previous week's 10.134 percent and 10.638 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the peso weakened slightly against the dollar during
the week of March 17-21, with average exchange rate recorded at
26.335 pesos against the dollar from the previous week's 26.3222
to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The governor said that the average exchange rate from January 2
to the current week stood at 26.3282 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Singson told President Ramos that the central
bank will remain vigilant in monitoring domestic and international
economic developments to ensure the implementation of timely and
appropriate policy responses.
</P>
<P>
Economists here said that by publishing Singson's report, the
government intends to dismiss rumours that a monetary crisis could
possibly hit the Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
