<HEADLINE> China-Invested Enterprises Optimistic About HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China-invested enterprises in
Hong Kong are quite optimistic about the future of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), said Gu Yongjiang, chairman
 of the Hong Kong Chinese Enterprises Association, at a seminar
held here today to mark the 7th anniversary of the promulgation of
 the Basic Law of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Gu said that the promotion of the prosperity of Hong Kong and
service to its community are the fundamental principles of the
China-invested enterprises in Hong Kong, who are active in
integrating into the Hong Kong society and contributing to the
economic prosperity and development of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said that following the development of China-invested
enterprises in Hong Kong, the economic linkage between Hong Kong
and the inland areas has been strengthened, and the "China factor"
in Hong Kong's economic activities has become more important than
ever.
</P>
<P>
He said reasons behind their optimism about the future of the
HKSAR are that the Basic Law provides a fundamental safeguard to
the social stability and economic prosperity of the HKSAR; the
economic development of the inland areas will inject a major
impetus to Hong Kong's continued economic development.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Hong Kong has well developed infrastructure, with
the gradual opening up of the financial and service markets of the
 inland areas, Hong Kong will enjoy tremendous economic
opportunities; as a major trade, aviation and financial service
center in the Asia-Pacific Region, Hong Kong will continue to
attract more foreign capitals and further develop foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
He noted that, after Hong Kong returns to the motherland,
China-invested enterprises in Hong Kong will enter into a new
phase of development.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, these enterprises will not enjoy any privileges,
 nor will they seek to dominate the economic activities of Hong
Kong," he said. "Rather, they will continue to observe the laws
and market regulations of Hong Kong, and positively participate in
 the competitions on an equal basis in the Hong Kong market."
</P>
<P>
He said China-invested enterprises will continue to explore
development opportunities through fair and healthy competition,
and will join efforts with foreign enterprises to further develop
Hong Kong and to build a better future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
