<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Situation Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China's financial situation was
stable during the first two months this year, according to an
analytical report by the People's Bank of China, the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Inflation remained at bay, with the retail price index edging
up 3.3 percent in January, and 2.9 percent in February. The
consumer price index went up 5.9 and 5.6 percent, respectively,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The money supply was on the downward trend during the two-month
period, due to a small increase in central bank investment, slower
growth in foreign exchange reserves, and redoubled efforts to
recover the central bank loans from the commercial banks. The
growth in money supply in February dropped to its lowest level
since 1994, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The growth in fixed-term deposits of enterprises has
slowed down this year, with the current deposits for the two-month
period dropping by more than 100 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The report also said the recent issue of government voucher
bonds impacted individual savings deposits, the growth of which
also slowed down compared with the 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
All financial markets had smooth operation and active trading
in the first two months this year, with the supply and demand of
short-term funds in near balance and a stable yuan, said the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
