<HEADLINE> Chinese President Calls For Closer Sino-Filipino Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin, in a
meeting with Ernesto Maceda, president of the Senate of the
Philippines, in Beijing today, said that China is willing to make
a concerted effort along with the Philippines for closer relations
in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
China treasures its friendship with the Philippines, he said,
and establishing long-term and stable bilateral ties is in accord
with the interests of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Jiang recalled his talks with Maceda during his visit last year
to the Philippines, and the exchange of opinions with President
Fidel Ramos on good neighbourliness and co-operation and other
issues of common concern. He said that at that time they reached
"consensus" on an extensive range of issues.
</P>
<P>
China and the Philippines, both developing countries, are faced
with the same task of developing the economy and improving the
standard of living, Jiang said, and that both need a stable
neighborly relationship and sound international environment.
</P>
<P>
The President expressed his appreciation and thanks for the
Philippines' support of China in human rights and its adherence to
the "One China" policy as concerns Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Friendship between the two countries can be traced back to
ancient times, Jiang noted, and since the establishment of
diplomatic ties, bilateral relations have seen smooth progress,
and exchanges of high-level visits have been frequent.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that in recent years, bilateral economic and
trade co-operation have grown rapidly, and communication in other
sectors has been quite active.
</P>
<P>
The President also briefed the Filipino guests on the two major
issues facing China this year, the 15th National Congress of the
Chinese Communist Party, and Hong Kong returning to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Jiang asked Maceda to convey his best regards to President
Ramos, and Maceda conveyed President Ramos' greetings to Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Maceda said Jiang's visit to the Philippines last year
contributed much to the safeguarding of peace and stability of the
region and to promoting good-neighborliness and co-operation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Filipino Senate plays an important role in the country's
foreign policy, and the Philippines will stick to the "One China"
policy and agrees with China in its stand on the human rights
issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
China and the Philippines have a long-standing traditional
friendship, Maceda said, and that he is happy to see that
bilateral ties have seen new progress in many important fields.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
