<HEADLINE> Food Price Pushes up Inflation in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- An inflation rate of 8.5 percent
up in March from 4.9 percent in February is registered in Uganda
due to the food price, "The New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Consumer price figures, released by Muwanga Zake, commissioner
for statistics from the Ministry of Planning and Economics
Development, indicated an increase of price of staple food
between 0.9 and 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Food prices in Kampala arose by 7.5 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The report released by the Ugandan authorities did not give
the reason of inflation in March, but businessmen here attributed
it to the current famine caused by the prolonged drought from
last November to late last March and the rain delayed up to
almost a whole month.
</P>
<P>
The highest inflation rate of 12.6 percent was witnessed in
Mbale District in the famine-hit east.
</P>
<P>
The prices of beverages, tobacco, clothes, fuel, household
goods, transport and communication and services were also up a
little bit. 
</P>
