<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Progress in Educational Sector in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China made new progress in its
educational field in 1996, especially in the reform of the
management system of higher education, and in the adjustment of
the structure of universities, according to an annual report by
the State Statistics Bureau published today.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, there were 1,032 general universities,
22 less than in the previous year; 1,138 institutions of adult
higher education, a decrease of 18 over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, institutions of higher education took in 966,000 new
undergraduate students, 40,000 up year-on-year, and the total
number of enrolled undergraduate students was 3,020,000. And the
total number of students taking graduate course was 162,000,
or an increase of 17,000 over 1995.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, there were 10.1 million students
studying in various kinds of secondary and technical schools.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, noticeable progress was made in the implementation of
the country's 9-year compulsory education program, the report says.
</P>
<P>
Some 50.48 million students in junior secondary schools, with
an enrollment rate of 82.4 percent, up four percentage points
year-on-year; and 136.15 million pupils in primary schools, with
an enrollment rate of 98.8 percent, an increase of 0.3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the drop-off rates of students in junior secondary
schools and primary schools stood at 3.5 percent and 1.3 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Hope Project, an national fund aimed to help students in
poor areas, received 290 million yuan in donations from home and
abroad, and helped 296,000 pupils return to school, while 1,560
primary schools were established under the Hope Project.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, noticeable headway was made in adult education, the
report says, noting that by the end of last year, there were 3.1
million students in adult secondary specialized schools, 83.37
million students in adult technical training schools.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4,070,000 people passed basic literacy courses last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
