<HEADLINE> India's Trade Deficit Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- India's trade deficit during the
April-February period of the fiscal year of 1996-97 reached 5.256
billion U.S. dollars, representing an increase of 2.2 billion
dollars over the corresponding period of the previous year, The
Times of India said today.
</P>
<P>
According to latest trade data released by the Indian Commerce
Ministry, the widening of the trade gap was a result of the sharp
slowdown in export growth to 5.61 percent during the period under
review.
</P>
<P>
During April-February, 1995-96, India's exports had notched up
a growth of 21.38 percent.
</P>
<P>
Import growth, which too had decelerated during the earlier
months of 1996-97, bounced back to record a 26.87 percent increase
in February over the same month of the previous financial year.
</P>
<P>
The pick up in import growth also aided the widening of trade
gap. 
</P>
</TEXT>
