<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Moves to Protect Rubber Seedlings Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Measures are expected to be taken
to ensure the survival of a rubber seedling bank in suburban
Jinghong of Yunnan Province, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The rubber seedling plantation, in the Yunnan Tropical Plants
Scientific Research Institute, is one of the country's largest
rubber seedling resource bases.
</P>
<P>
Set up in the 1960s, the bank had a collection of more than
4,000 new species from South American countries. Scientific
personnel have developed a series of them suitable for growth in
China.
</P>
<P>
But large areas of the seedlings are beginning to die due to
the foul smoke and fumes from surrounding brickyards. By last
year, more than 267 hectares and been infected, nearly half of the
total.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government, and scientific and environmental
protection departments have paid immense attention to the
deteriorating situation and are determined to effectively protect
the rubber seedlings.
</P>
<P>
They called for taking effective measures to protect the rubber
seedlings.
</P>
<P>
The Land Reclamation Bureau, under the Ministry of Agriculture,
has urged its local bureaux to cooperate with local authorities
and solve the problem as quick as possible.
</P>
<P>
Local environment protection authorities in January ordered the
brickyards to pay 500,000 yuan (60,000 US dollars) and put their
fluoride discharge under control.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has more than 147,000 hectares of rubber tree
plantations, and rubber has become the province's fourth largest
economic pillar after cigarettes, sugar and tea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Ports of Entry Facilitate Trade and Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China has opened a total of 235
land, railway and air ports of entry to foreign passengers and
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Among these outlets, classified as Category One, six were newly
opened in 1996, including an airport in Mudianjiang City of
Heilongjiang Province, a railway outlet for cargo in Harbin,
capital of Heilongjiang, a sea port in Zhejiang Province, two sea
ports in Shandong Province, and a river port in Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
There are also 350 Category Two ports of entry catering to
Chinese foreign trade vehicles and border trade.
</P>
<P>
"These ports of entry are contributing increasingly to the
growing foreign trade, tourism, and international exchanges", an
official of the State Port of Entry Office reported at a meeting
today.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the ports of entry in China handled a total of 369
million tons of foreign trade goods, about the same as the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Sea and river ports played a main role, accounting for 314
million tons of the goods handled; highway cargo totalled 43.95
million tons; railway cargo reached 9.55 million tons; and 515,000
tons were handled by airports.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the ports of entry dealt with a total of 118.59
million passengers coming in or going out of the country, a rise
of 8.98 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 92.54 million people passed through land outlets,
13.72 million through airports, and 12.33 million through sea and
river ports.
</P>
<P>
As China has shifted its efforts from increasing the number of
ports of entry to improving the service of the existing ones, the
customs, frontier inspection, commodity inspection, and
quarantine--the sectors involved in a port of entry--have all
improved their work by simplifying procedures and standardizing
management, according to a work report distributed at the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
