mineral deposits in 152 places through geological surveys in
1996, according to the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
A communique released by the bureau today shows that 1996 also
saw the preparation of 276 important reports on geological surveys
that could be used for industrial and agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Forty-two minerals were found to have increased reserves,
including 661.09 million tons of petroleum, 141.67 billion cu m of
natural gas, 3.5 billion tons of coal, 228 tons of gold
(including grade E reserve), 89.82 million tons of iron ore, and
22.92 million tons of sulfuric ores.
</P>
<P>
The communique added that geological prospecting enterprises
completed a total of 5.45 million m of drilling in the past
year. 
