<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Nations Sign Declaration on Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Environment ministers of the
governments of South Asian countries decided at the conclusion of
a two-day meeting here on Thursday to establish an information
exchange network on data and policies, The Times of India said
today.
</P>
<P>
This was approved as part of a joint declaration on environment
policy signed by ministers of the seven South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) countries.
</P>
<P>
The declaration will be presented on behalf of the seven
countries (India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan
and Maldives) at the June meeting in New York of the United
Nations' general assembly to review progress on the decisions
taken at the U.N. meeting on the environment at Rio, Brazil, in
1991.
</P>
<P>
In the "New Delhi Declaration," the SAARC ministers reiterated
that actions should be taken to check toxic waste imports, protect
biodiversity, manage marine pollution and resource-sustainability.
</P>
<P>
They demanded that developed nations transfer regularly far
more funds for the protection of environment than they have ever
been wont to.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed to a proposal from the Economic
Development Institution of the World Bank to organize a
"high-level" policy training program among SAARC countries on
mainstream environmentally sustainable programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
