<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: No Compromise on Settlement Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 4 (Xinhua) -- With three days ahead of his
visit to the United States, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu vowed not to bow to any pressure on the issue of
settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Thursday night to a meeting of the ruling Likud
Party's chiefs, Netanyahu said the construction of the
controversial Har Homa housing project in East Jerusalem would
proceed as planned, and so would work in other settlements in the
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
He also gave a tough message to the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) that he would take "non-diplomatic alternatives"
if the PNA failed to halt the terrorist attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate, but adding that he "will not act rashly."
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office said Netanyahu would give the
messages to U.S. President Bill Clinton when they meet
Monday. Netanyahu would stress that there would be no peace
process unless the PNA cracked down on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
However, the Palestinians have also made it clear that the
Israelis must stop settlement construction before peace talks
could be resumed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is reportedly considering requesting Netanyahu to halt
the Har Homa construction for six months as a good-will gesture
to rescue the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu continued accusing PNA President Yasser Arafat of
giving a green light to terrorism. He said Arafat not only gave
the green light, but also "is issuing demands for switching it
off." The Palestinian leader has rejected the accusation.
</P>
<P>
"No amount of pressure will make Israel veer from its policy
that terror cannot be considered a legitimate tool of
negotiations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will absolutely not capitulate to terror or to threats of
terror and will continue construction in Jerusalem and Judea and
Samaria (West Bank)," he added.
</P>
<P>
In reaction, the PA strongly denounced Netanyahu for "issuing a
new declaration to cancel the peace process." Senior Palestinian
negotiator Hasan Asfour described Netanyahu's statements as "a
new stone on the grave of the political process."
</P>
<P>
"It is a message to the U.S. that it has become necessary for
the U.S. administration to react to these rude demands," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat slammed Israel for threatening to torpedo the peace
process with continued confiscation of Palestinian land for
expanding Jewish settlements. Arafat convened top PNA officials
in Gaza Thursday night to discuss the stalemate in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu plans to travel Sunday to the United States. He is
to hold a meeting with Jordanian King Hussein, who is currently
visiting the U.S. while undergoing a prostate surgery in
Rochester of Minnesota. Then he will hold talks with President
Clinton in Washington on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
