<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rita Fan on Future Political System of HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- It is both prudent and pragmatic
 to develop a democratic political system in Hong Kong in a
gradual and orderly way, said Rita Fan, president of the
Provisional Legislature of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), today at a seminar marking the 7th anniversary of
the promulgation of the Basic Law of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
She said that the concept of "one country, two systems" and the
 policy of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" outlined in the
Basic Law clearly represents the Central Government's high degree
of confidence in Hong Kong people's ability and wisdom.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the existing and future political structures of
Hong Kong are fundamentally different. For example, the Chief
Executive of the SAR is elected by a Selection Committee composed
of 400 Hong Kong permanent residents, while throughout the 150
years of British rule in Hong Kong, the governor was invariably
appointed by the British Government without any consultation with
the people of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Under the future political system of Hong Kong, the fundamental
 policy of "the legislature lending cooperation to and also acting
 as checks and balances on the executive-led government" will be
given expression. The Legislature of the HKSAR possesses more
power than the current Legislative Council. The former possesses
the authority to impeach the Chief Executive, while the latter
cannot challenge the status of the Governor of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
She said that when the British side implemented its "reform
package" and hence derailed the through train mechanism of the
current Legislative Council, the establishment of the Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC) is the only way to avoid the emergence
of the legal vacuum and it is also consistent with the principle
of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Before July 1, 1997, the PLC will scrutinize and pass
legislation needed for the proper establishment and functioning of
 the Hong Kong SAR. As the legislative powers and legal bases of
the PLC and the current Legislative Council stem from different
legal systems and constitutions, their scopes of work are
different, there is no question of their roles overlapping, she
stressed.
</P>
<P>
"In 88 days, Hong Kong returns to the motherland, the SAR is
born and the Basic Law goes into effect. The political system
outlined in the Basic Law offers true democracy and higher degree
of participation for Hong Kong people. I have full reason to
believe that Hong Kong people are able to manage Hong Kong well,"
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12th NAM Ministerial Meeting Opens in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The 12th Ministerial Conference
of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) countries opened here today when
senior officials of these countries began discussions to finalize
the agenda for the foreign ministerial meeting on April 7-8.
</P>
<P>
The senior officials, who is meeting for two days, will also
finalize draft documents on political and economic issues for the
considerations of the foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from at least 70 NAM member countries have
confirmed their participation while the rest of the nations will
be presented at the level of ministers of state and ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
Nam presently has 112 members, excluding Yugoslavia, the
membership of which is suspended.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Anna will address the NAM foreign
ministers' meeting on April 7. 
</P>
