<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Structure of Assets Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- As macro-economic environment
improved and enterprise reform proceeded, the structure of assets
and liabilities for enterprises improved in 1996 and the value of
industrial capital was preserved and increased.
</P>
<P>
A communique released by the State Statistics Bureau
today shows that the debt ratio of industrial
enterprises was 65.2 percent, of which, that of state-owned
enterprises was 65.6 percent, both dropping to some extent as
compared with that in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Capital value of industrial enterprises at the end of the year
was 119.6 percent as compared with that at the beginning of the
year, of which that of state-owned enterprises was 118.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The prominent problems existing in the industrial production
were the irrational structure and the difficulty in the management
and the production of some of the enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The communique explained that though the production
and marketing situation improved quarter by quarter, the sales
ratio of the whole year was still one to two percentage points
lower than the normal year.
</P>
<P>
The stock of products and the arrears among enterprises were
not alleviated. By the end of 1996, the stock of manufactured
goods increased by over 75 billion yuan over that the beginning
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The net volume of debts outstanding increased by 120 billion
yuan. The losses incurred to some enterprises were serious, and
the proportion of loss-making enterprises was 23 percent, up by
1.7 percentage points, and the volume of losses accounted for 24.8
percent of the total profits and taxes made, up by 6.2 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
The communique noted that the quality of industrial operation
should be further improved.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Improve Foreign Investment Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China is going to make an effort
to put more foreign investment into infrastructure, basic
industries, high technology, value-added industries, and large key
projects, according to the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
It expects to look for direct foreign investment of 230 billion
to 270 billion US dollars during the Ninth Five-Year Plan period
(1996-2000). So far, China has used 177 billion dollars worth of
foreing investment since it adopted the reform and opening up
policy in the late 1970s, ranking first among the developing
countries in terms of the scale of using foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Departments will take steps to use foreign investment in
industrial structure and economic layout adjustments, and to give
foreign-funded enterprises equal treatment as their Chinese
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
China will further reduce import tariffs, reform its import and
export controls, revise its Guiding Directory on Industries Open
to Foreign Investment items, and expand the BOT
(build-operate-transfer) investment scheme.
</P>
<P>
Areas that are open to foreign investment include agricultural
new technology, opening up land, water conservation, energy,
transportation, raw and processed materials, machinery,
electronics, and mining.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the service trade will be done in a
planned way, and an effort will be made to focus on residential
housing and tighten real estate controls.
</P>
<P>
Measures will be developed to improve the foreign investment
structure. Of the foreign investment in the past, half went to the
ordinary processing industry, 30 percent to hotels and real
estate, and only 1.5 percent and 1.8 percent to agriculture and
transportation, respectively. Less than 10 percent went to the
basic industries like electric power and petroleum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
