<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Construction Industry Thriving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China's construction industry
generated 456.8 billion yuan in added value in 1996, up by 8.6
percent over 1995, according to the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
A communique released by the bureau shows that the reform of
the construction industry was further improved in 1996, and the
bidding system was also perfected and expanded.
</P>
<P>
The total number of projects under construction by state-owned
construction enterprises reached 214,000. Of the total, 82,000
were constructed through the bidding system, accounting for 38.2
percent of the total, or 4.5 percentage points higher than that in
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The management of the construction market was further improved
and the system of the construction market was also improved. The
total added value of state-owned construction enterprises was
116.9 billion yuan, the growth rate kept the same pace as compared
with that in the previous year. The overall labor productivity was
15,050 yuan, up by 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The floor space of buildings completed during the year was 140
million sq m, down by 9.6 percent. The total profits and taxes
made were 11.75 billion yuan, with the per capita profits and
taxes amounting to 1,600 yuan, or maintaining the same level over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of loss-making enterprises in the construction
industry increased, the communique said, noting that improvement
should be made in the economic efficiency of the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
