<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa-Malaysia Helicopter Deal Yet Finalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's leading arms
manufacturer Denel denied on Thursday that the proposed purchase
of eight Rooivalk attack helicopters by Malaysia had been
finalized.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at a maritime defense exhibition at the
Simonstown Navy Base, Denel Chief Executive Johan Alberts said
his company was still persuading Malaysia to buy the Rooivalks
but no deal had been signed yet, reported a local daily "The
Citizen" today.
</P>
<P>
Alberts said: "We know that the Malaysians are interested, we
know they have made positive sounds, but there are still a lot of
things we must do."
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Malaysia was negotiating with Denel to
buy eight Rooivalks, and the first two helicopters were expected
to be delivered soon.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's national news agency Bernama last month quoted
Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar as saying that the proposed
Rooivalk deal, the first to be sold outside South Africa, would
be the core for future expansion of the Rooivalk fleet in the
country's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia was reportedly planning to buy 30 Rooivalks from
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Simonstown defense exhibition is being held as part of
celebrations to mark the 75th anniversary of the South African
Navy. Ships or representatives from about 30 countries are
attending the exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
