<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Insurance Industry Makes Big Progress in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China's insurance industry has
achieved farly big progress in 1996, the State Statistics Bureau
said in its annual report today.
</P>
<P>
The total insured value jumped by 10.4 percent over the
previous year to 15,664.5 billion yuan worth in 1996, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the insurance premium reached 75.6 billion yuan, up
20.5 percent over the previous year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, the premium of property insurance was 44.5
billion yuan, while that of life insurance stood at 31.1 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The insurance companies paid an indemnity of 25.9 billion yuan
in property insurance programs, and anther 5.5 billion yuan in
life insurance programs.
</P>
<P>
China also marched a large step forward in its social security
reform last year, with its nationwide old-age pension system
already covering 87.6 million workers and government staff, and
22.8 billion retired people receiving social welfare pensions.
</P>
<P>
Over 18 million government staff and workers took part in a
reformed social medicare security program in 1996, with more than
one million retired staff and workers engaged in a similar plan.
</P>
<P>
Chinese peoples also received better protection against
unemployment, with the labor insurance agencies at all levels
providing unemployment relief to some three million jobless people.
</P>
<P>
A rural social security network also took shape in over 34
percent of the townships and counties in China, said the report,
which already covered more than 62.66 million rural population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
