<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Enjoy Higher Living Standard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese people's living standard
improved in 1996, according to a communique released by the
State Statistics Bureau today.
</P>
<P>
The household income continued to increase steadily. The annual
per capita disposable income and income for living expenses of
urban households were 4,839 yuan and 4,377 yuan, respectively, in
1996, up 3.8 percent and 3.3 percent in real term.
</P>
<P>
The per capita income of rural households was 1,926 yuan, up 22
percent, and the real growth was nine percent if price hike was
deducted.
</P>
<P>
The communique admitted that unbalanced development among
regions and among different groups of population was still
evident, and the real income of some households in some
provinces and regions declined to some extent.
</P>
<P>
Labor and employment situation was basically stable last year,
said the communique. By the end of last year, the number of total
employed people in China reached 688.5 million, an increase of
nine million over 1995. The number of registered urban unemployed
persons was 5.53 million in China in 1996, with an unemployment
rate of three percent.
</P>
<P>
Total wage bill of staff and worker continued to increase. The
average annual wages of employees in urban areas were 6,210 yuan,
up 12.9 percent, with a real growth of 3.8 percent if price
increase was excluded.
</P>
<P>
Urban and rural living conditions further improved, with a
total of 360 million square meters of new residential buildings
completed in urban areas, and 760 million square meters of new
houses built in rural areas in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Social welfare undertakings developed steadily. At the end of
1996, ther were 1,020,000 beds in social welfare institutions of
various types in China, with 770,000 inmates.
</P>
<P>
The community service network continued to expand in urban
areas and reform of social relief system further developed, said
the communique. Statistics show that the minimum life guarantee
system had been established in 101 cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
