<HEADLINE> China Develops Transportation and Telecommunications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China is reported to earn more
than 381 billion yuan in added value from transportation and
telecommunications industries last year, a 9.1 percent rise from
the previous year, according to the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In terms of transportion, China's cargo-handling volume was
lifted 1.5 percent from the year 1995 to surpass 3,627 billion
ton-kilometers in 1996, with the passenger transport volume rising
3.7 percent over 1995 to reach 933.7 billion person-kilometers.
</P>
<P>
And the total handling capacity of the country's major harbors
rose 4.1 percent over 1995 to reach 835 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Business transactions of the country's postal and
telecommunication services totalled 133.5 billion yuan in 1996, up
35.4 percent from 1995,
</P>
<P>
The handling capacity of telephone switchboards in the
country's urban and rural areas reached 108.64 million lines. And
the capacity of office telephone switchboards rose by 21.07
million lines over 1995 to reach 93.185 million lines in 1996,
nearly 99.5 percent of which were program-controlled.
</P>
<P>
China added 17.45 million telephone users in 1996, bringing the
total number to 61.79 million. There was an average of 6.33
telephones for every 100 people in the country in 1996, or 1.67
percentage points higher than the 1995 figure.
</P>
<P>
More than 53 percent of the country's administrative villages,
or over 394,000 administrative villages, had access to telephone
systems in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The country added 3.22 million mobile phone subscribers in
1996, bringing the total to 6.85 million.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 users of computer network service, group switchboard
service and digital data transmission service rose 370 percent, 98
percent and 200 percent over the 1995 figure, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
