<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Conduct Further Probe on Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Security and Exchange Commission
(SEC) of Bangladesh would make further investigations against some
of the stock brokers and directors of listed companies whose name
were mentioned in the probe report on share market scam.
</P>
<P>
The SEC sources said here today that the investigation will be
conducted on the extent of involvement of some influential stock
brokers in the massive fraud unearthed by a SEC committee headed
by Amirul Islam.
</P>
<P>
Receiving the report on the unprecedented ups and downs on the
stock market starting from last July, the SEC on Wednesday filed
cases against eight listed companies and seven brokers-dealers on
charge of fraudulent act and unethical activities towards market
manipulation.
</P>
<P>
The court on the same day issued 36 warrants of arrest against
32 persons including chairman and directors of the accused
companies and broker-dealer houses.
</P>
<P>
However, there was no arrest till today and four directors of
two suspected companies on Thursday got anticipatory bail from a
division bench of the High Court.
</P>
<P>
On the stock market, the benchmark Dhaka Stock Exchange all
share price index on Thursday plunged to 1138.09 point registering
a massive 7.13 percent or 87 points slide.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some top businessmen on Thursday hoped that the
SEC's move will end a serious turmoil in the market to enable it
to play the expected role to contribute to the country's
development.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce and
Industry (MCCI) and Foreign Investors Chamber of Commerce and
Industry (FICCI) noted that the publication of the probe report
will now stabilize the capital market plagued by scandals.
</P>
<P>
The MCCI President Samson Chowdhury and the FICCI President
Mahbub Amil in the statement also expected that the publication of
the inquiry committee report would vindicate the feelings of
thousands of investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
