<HEADLINE> Chile, Brazil Strike Deal on Import Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Brazil has agreed to give exports
from Chile the same exemptions from its recently-imposed import
restrictions as other members of the Mercosur trade bloc, Chilean
Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Insulza said today.
</P>
<P>
He said a partial agreement has been reached to exempt Chile,
an associate member of the four-nation Mercosur bloc, from
Brazil's new regulations which demand that imports be paid for in
cash by importers as soon as goods enter the country.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, a member of Mercosur, announced yesterday that it had
reached a temporary deal with Argentina over exemptions from the
new requirements, which would also cover Uruguay and Paraguay, the
other members of Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
The restrictions were announced last week as part of Brazil's
attempt to cut its trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement with Chile, between 10,000 and 40,000
U.S. dollars of Chilean products will be exempt from restrictions
on payment terms.
</P>
<P>
The deal will be in force for 120 days, when an evaluation
will be made to decide on additional measures.
</P>
<P>
Insulza said Economy Minister Alvaro Garcia and Juan Gabriel
Valdes, director of international economic relations of the
Foreign Ministry, left for Brazil today to hammer out the details.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is Chile's third largest trading partner.
</P>
<P>
Last year Chile imported 1.07 billion dollars worth of products
and exported 934.05 million dollars of goods, running a deficit
of 131.16 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
