<HEADLINE> Italy, Albania Start Joint Sea Patrols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Italy is to send a light fleet to
Albania's Adriatic coast to safeguard and strengthen security in
the area.
</P>
<P>
Under a protocol signed today in Rome between the two
countries, an Albanian contingent will be on all ships patrolling
the Adriatic sea which is the main route being used by refugees to
flee Albania which has been gripped by violence and unrest since
February.
</P>
<P>
Several more ships loaded with refugees were reportedly heading
for Italy today from the southern Albanian ports of Vlore and
Durres.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Italian Defense Minister Beniamino
Andreatta and his Albanian counterpart Shakir Vukaj at a meeting
of 70 military representatives and diplomats from 10 countries
ready to send troops to Albania.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting also discussed the details of
deploying a U.N.-approved multinational protection force (MPF) due
to arrive in Albania by April 12 to protect food aid and other
humanitarian relief and carry out logistical operations.
</P>
<P>
Italy is expected to contribute 2,000-2,500 troops, France
1,000, Greece 700, Spain 500, Turkey 500 and Romania 400 to the
MPF. 
</P>
