<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Trade Expands, Structure Improves in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade expands in
scale last year with a better import and export structure,
according a report from China's State Statistics Bureau (SSB)
released here today.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of export and import reached 289.9 billion US
dollars, up 3.2 percent over the previous year, of which the value
of export was 151.1 billion dollars, up 1.5 percent, and the value
of import was 138.8 billion dollars, an increase of 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the SSB, the structure of import and export was
further improved. The shares of mechanical and electronic products
in the export rose from 29.5 percent in 1995 to 31.9 percent last
year, remaining the largest category of export commodities.
</P>
<P>
In the realm of import, significant increase was seen in the
import of raw materials, energy products and transport means that
were in short at domestic market.
</P>
<P>
China also made progress in diversifying import and export
channels. The value of trade with Oceania and Latin America
increased by 19.7 percent and 10 percent, respectively, far better
than the growth in trade with other continents, the SSB said.
</P>
</TEXT>
