<HEADLINE> OSCE will Head International Aid Mission in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The mission to send a multinational
force and humanitarian and economic assistance to strife-torn
Albania will be led by the Organization of Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), former Austrian Chancellor Franz
Vranitzky said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, Vranitzky, who is also the OSCE's
special envoy to Albania, said the OSCE's leadership has been
agreed by Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi, his Albanian
counterpart Bashkim Fino and Dutch Foreign Minister Hans van
Mierlo, whose country now holds the rotating six-month presidency
of the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Vranitzky said the EU is expected to provide humanitarian and
economic aid while the OSCE and Council of Europe will be
responsible for June's parliamentary elections and the drafting of
a new Albanian constitution.
</P>
<P>
The 5,000-strong Italian-led multinational protection force
(MPF), consisting of troops from Italy, France, Greece, Austria,
Spain, Turkey and Romania, is to guarantee the security of the
whole mission.
</P>
<P>
Austria will send up to 120 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The details of the MPF are yet to be finalized, but
Vranitzky, the mission controller, said the previously agreed
deployment date of April 12 "may be optimistic".
</P>
<P>
He also said general elections in Albania will be held in the
middle of this year. Although the country was still in chaos and
the situation was very complicated, he didn't agree with delaying
the elections.
</P>
<P>
A panel of OSCE experts have arrived in Tirana today to
start the preparation work for the election, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
