<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Alert on Coconut Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua's coconut plantations
are threatened by the arrival of an exotic plant disease already
detected in Honduras, as reported by the local press.
</P>
<P>
The rust, that attacks the coconut palms, called "lethal
yellowing of the coconut," could propagate in Nicaragua and
exterminate the coconut plantations, mainly in the Atlantic
region, where the fruits of this plant are used for the
manufacture of vegetable oil.
</P>
<P>
The virus has already exterminated some coconut plantations in
Cuba, Haiti, and the Dominican Republic, and other Caribbean
countries, and was detected recently in the Honduran island of
Roatan.
</P>
<P>
Specialists in plant diseases say the plague advances 100
kilometers per year, which means that the Nicaraguan authorities
and owners of coconut plantations should right away start thinking
of the way to save or substitute the coconut palms.
</P>
<P>
According to the specialists, the lethal yellowing of the
coconut palm is transmitted by a kind of insects that jump from
leaf to leaf. Another way of propagation of the disease is by the
transportation of sick plants or coconut products.
</P>
<P>
This situation has prompted the Nicaraguan Agriculture and
Livestock Ministry to request agriculturists, merchants, and the
public in general, not to bring to Nicaragua coconut plants from
other countries without the sanitary authorization of the
ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Reduce Imports of Oil Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia's energy industry plans to
slash imports of oil equipment from abroad to shake off its
dependence on foreign deliveries, Vladimir Kurashov, an official
from the Fuel Ministry, said today.
</P>
<P>
Russian energy companies import between six and seven billion
U.S. dollars of equipment a year. But Kurashov said some of the
imports could be substituted with domestic goods, as many defense
companies have now turned to making equipment for the oil and gas
industry.
</P>
<P>
Kurashov was speaking at a news conference ahead of the
international "Oil and Gas '97" exhibition which starts in Moscow
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kurashov told reporters the ministry has worked out a
program to reduce fuel exports by a third -- from the
current 30 percent to 20 percent. The figure should eventually
fall to 10-15 percent, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
