<HEADLINE> Thailand to Allow More Foreign Holdings in local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to allow more
foreign holdings in new finance firms emerging after mergers in a
bid to promote mergers in the ailing finance sector.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Amnuay Virawan recently has said
that the new firms of this kind are an exception, but foreign
holdings in local commercial banks and other financial
institutions will remain limited up to five percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign stake in the new firms may not exceed 25
percent, stressed Amnuay, who also serves as finance minister.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry will consider allowing foreign financial
institutions to merge with Thai finance companies on a
case-by-case basis, Amnuay was quoted as saying by local
newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that foreign financial institutions may not
be keen in merging business in Thailand as they are focusing on
raising capital in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
