<HEADLINE> Honduran Blacks Mark 2nd Centennial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Black people in Honduras begin
celebrating, on Friday, the second centennial of their ancestors'
arrival.
</P>
<P>
Celebrations will include academic, religious and cultural
activities.
</P>
<P>
The first blacks arrived here in 1797, after being banished by
the French and the British from the San Vicente Islands in the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
The blacks, estimated at 300,000 in Honduras, have maintained
their customs and live from fishing and the cultivation of yucca,
bananas and coconuts. 
