<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More than 100,000 AIDS Cases Detected in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- About 105,000 cases of AIDS
had been detected in Brazil by February this year, a 10 percent
increase over November of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The latest three monthly figures released by the Brazilain
Health Ministry show AIDS has spread rampantly in Brazil in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Brazil has the highest number of AIDS cases in Latin America,
and the health ministry estimates there are at least 500,000
cases, the majority of them undetected, throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Pedro Chequer, coordinator of the National Program for Venereal
Diseases, said most AIDS cases were detected in the most
economically advanced regions, like the states of Sao Paulo, Rio
de Janeiro, and Minas Gerais.
</P>
<P>
Brazil registered its first case of AIDS in 1980, and the
number shot up to 82,852 by last May and to 88,099 in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
