<HEADLINE> Indonesia Plans to Promote Non-oil Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
continue to encourage the country's non-oil/non-gas exports which
have been going down lately, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"Our non-oil exports have declined as a consequence of smaller
need of importing countries, the emergence of competitors and an
appreciation of the rupiah against the US dollar," Industry and
Trade Minister Tunky Ariwibowo said Thursday after meeting
President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's non-oil and gas export growth was only 9 percent a
year, less than the 15 percent to 19 percent targeted in the
current five-year development plan, official sources of the
Industry and Trade Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
They quoted Tunky as saying that the government was formulating
steps to boost the growth of non-oil exports.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government would provide financial
support to exporters.
</P>
<P>
The government was also planning to increase the number of
trade promotion centers abroad from 13 to 23 and the number of
trade attaches from 25 to 33, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tunky also disclosed that Indonesia posted a trade surplus of
575.4 million US dollars in January, 37.2 percent lower than in
December last year, but 38.1 percent higher compared to a year
earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
