<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Situation Stable in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China's financial situation was
basically stable last year, the State Statistics Bureau (SSB) said
today in its annual report.
</P>
<P>
China has made positive result in modifying interest rate last
year, with the financial reform further deepened, financial
supervision and management enhanced, and financial regulatory
measures improved, said the SSB report.
</P>
<P>
The savings deposits in various forms in financial institutions
totalled 6,859.6 billion yuan in 1996, an increase of 1,479.2
billion yuan, or up 27.3 percent, over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, savings of enterprises accounted for 2,245
billion yuan, 502.6 billion yuan or 29.6 percent more than the
1995 figure.
</P>
<P>
The savings deposits by urban and rural residents reached
3,852.1 billion yuan, up 880.5 billion yuan, or 29.9 percent, from
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding loans increased by 1,068.3 billion yuan, or
21.2 percent, to 6,115.7 billion yuan worth in 1996, according to
the SSB.
</P>
<P>
The report said the credit structure further improved in 1996.
On an annual basis, the amount of outstanding short-term loans
climbed by 665.3 billion yuan to 4,021 billion yuan, with the
amount of middle and long-term loans increasing by 204.1 billion
yuan to 1,267.3 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Money in circulation (M0) in 1996 grew by 91.7 billion yuan,
or 11.6 percent, over the previous year, to 880.2 billion yuan,
according to the report. The growth of narrow money (M1), which
includes currency in circulation plus enterprises' current
deposits, was 18.9 percent, and the broad money (M2) -- currency
plus all kinds of deposits -- increased by 25.3 percent over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The report said China's securities market was comparatively
active last year, reporting success in issuance and redemption of
the state treasury bonds. The nation's two stock markets listed a
total of 170 new A stocks last year, raising 23.53 billion yuan of
capital.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign exchange reserves increased by a relatively big
margin in 1996, rising by 31.4 billion US dollars to 105 billion
dollars, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
