<HEADLINE> Albanian PM Appeals for National Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Albania's government for national
reconciliation is the country's last hope of keeping the Balkan
country united, Prime Minister Bashkim Fino said today after a
two-day visit to Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian government is a government for national
reconciliation not for hatred, Fino said following his return from
a tour of Albanian refugee camps in Greece where some 300,000
people are estimated to be living.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister met leaders of Greece, the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) and the European Union
(EU) to secure much-needed support for the country which has been
gripped by near anarchy over the last month.
</P>
<P>
EU, OSCE and Greek officials are believed to have assured Fino
that his all-party unity government would get economic,
organizational and humanitarian aid, as well as the peacekeepers
needed to distribute it.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Albanians have fled to Italy and Greece over the
past three weeks as violence escalated in the country and armed
rebels took over several southern towns demanding the resignation
of President Sali Berisha.
</P>
<P>
The troubles were sparked by last December's collapse of
pyramid investment schemes in which thousands of Albanians lost
their life savings.  
</P>
