<HEADLINE> China Reports Steady Economic Growth in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China's national economy
registered a sustained and rapid development in the year 1996,
with the growth rate of gross domestic product (GDP) hitting 9.7
percent, a relatively high level in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
The State Statistics Bureau (SSB) today released the
"Statistical Communique of the People's Republic of China on 1996
National Economic and Social Development," saying that the Chinese
economy grew in a steady manner and the targets of major
macro-economic control were achieved last year.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference today, Zhang Sai, director of the SSB,
said that in 1996 the GDP of the country reached 6,779.5 billion
yuan, up 9.7 percent from that of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Of this total, the value-added of the primary industry was
1,355 billion yuan, up 5.1 percent; that of the secondary industry
3,314.8 billion yuan, up 12.3 percent; and that of the tertiary
industry 2,109.7 billion yuan, up eight percent.
</P>
<P>
The per capita GDP was 5,569 yuan, and the per capita
productivity of the whole society was 9,902 yuan, with a real
growth of 8.6 percent and 8.3 percent respectively over that in
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
However, the problems of irrational economic structure and
difficulties in management and operation encountered by some
enterprises were still prominent.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that such a robust growth in the national economy
reflected the vitality of market mechanism as well as an enhanced
macro-control capacity of the central government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
