<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crash Pilots Barred from Leaving Honduras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Two United States pilots who
survived the crash of a U.S. Air Force cargo plane on Tuesday at
the Toncotin International Airport, in Tegucigalpa, were
prohibited from leaving Honduras pending further investigation.
</P>
<P>
The pilots could not leave before reports on the accident were
known because they might be required by the courts to make
statements, said executive judge Dagoberto Aspra Iglesias.
</P>
<P>
One requirement was the examination of blood and urine samples
of survivors to determine whether they had consumed alcohol or
psychotropic substances before the accident.
</P>
<P>
Three people were killed and another seven injured when the
Hercules C-130 plane crashed in flames Tuesday morning after
over-running a landing strip at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the court said Judge Iglesias wanted to question
the pilots this morning at the military hospital where they are
being cared for. But U.S. agents in charge of the pilots did not
permit the judge to talk to them, and mentioned bilateral
migratory agreements between the United States and Honduras.
</P>
<P>
"That is an abuse, because the accident occurred in Honduran
territory and they must respect the laws of the country," said the
judge.
</P>
<P>
It was rumoured that the two injured pilots could be sent back
to the United States today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Army Southern Command, with headquarters in Panama,
sent 25 people to Honduras, with agents and medical personnel
among them, to start preliminary investigations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
