<HEADLINE> Canada Reviews Human Rights Position on China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada is reconsidering its
long-standing support of human-rights resolutions criticizing
China at the United Nations Human Rights Commission in Geneva,
Canadian leading newspaper the Globe and Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
Such resolutions have been backed by Canada every year at the
commission's annual review since 1989. Now, Canadian government
sources say Canada is reassessing its position, reported the
newspaper in its special dispatch from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
France has decided it will no longer co-sponsor the resolution,
saying China has made progress in some areas of human rights.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, the French decision really throws any possibility of
a resolution being passed into real doubt," Canadian Foreign
Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy told reporters in Beijing
Wednesday, saying "we have to make an assessment. I just found out
about the French decision this morning."
</P>
<P>
However, one Canadian government official close to the
situation told the newspaer that Germany, Italy and Spain were
already thinking of joining France on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have to reassess the situation," the official said.
</P>
<P>
A Canadian decision to end backing for the resolution would be
in keeping with Canada's evolving, soft-sell approach to the
status of human rights in China, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Pressure doesn't work, Axworthy declared, after several
hours of meetings with top Chinese leaders during his one-day
blitz of Beijing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
