<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infant Mortality in Peru Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Infant mortality in Peru has fallen
by 25 percent over the past five years, the National Statistics
and Informatics Institute (INEI) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The infant death rate has dropped from 57 in every 1,000 in
1987-1991 to 43 per thousand in 1991-1996.
</P>
<P>
But the figure conceals a wide differential between rural and
urban areas. The countryside has the highest rate of infant
mortality at an average of 71 in every 1,000, while the rate in
towns and cities is down at 35 per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
Women in Peru are also having fewer children. The birth rate
among women of child-bearing age fell from 3.9 in 1991 to 3.5 in
1996, the institute said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
