<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment Increases in North Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- An improved investment
environment in Qinhuangdao, in north China's Hebei Province, has
made the coastal city more attractive to overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The Qinhuangdao Development Zone, one of the first group of 14
state-level zones approved by the State Council in 1984, has
become a popular investment spot and a new source of economic
growth in the city, after more than 10 years of construction work.
</P>
<P>
The Zone added 61 foreign-funded enterprises in 1996, bringing
the total to more than 300. It used more than 80 million US
dollars in foreign investment last year, a 23 percent rise from
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
It has now attracted more than 1.4 billion US dollars worth of
overseas investment from 24 countries and regions, including the
US, France, Japan, ROK, Australia and Singapore, as well as Hong
Kong and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The overseas investment has helped the zone build a complete
industrial system centered on metallurgy, machinery, electronics,
textiles, fine petrochemicals, and building materials. 
</P>
