<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artillery Shelling to Prevent Hail Successful in Gansu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 10,000 artillery shells
have been fired to disperse hailstorms in Pingliang City in
northwest China's Gansu Province, protecting about 1,300 ha of
farmland from hail in the past ten years, according to the Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The city, located in a mountainous area, is prone to
hailstorms, and the Lanzhou Plateau Atmosphere Research Institute
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences has been entrusted with
disaster relief since 1986.
</P>
<P>
The institute has succeeded in dispersing hailstorms by
shelling clouds, with a total success rate of 94 percent. It has
done this for 178 times. Each bombardment used about 58 shells.
</P>
<P>
According to the evaluations of the local agricultural and
statistics departments, the shelling on average saved grain
production worth 2.7 million yuan (about 310,000 US dollars) each
year.
</P>
<P>
The institute has pioneered work on artificially changing
weathers in China. It will continue its research in the Pingliang
area and conduct experiments to alter storm patterns by inducing
lightning by artificial means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Strengthen Control on Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China will shift its focus to the
administration of existing ports from opening new ones in the
past, the country's Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua said at an annual
national conference on port administration Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The focus for 1997 will be placed on realizing a reasonable
layout of ports and improving port management, Zou was quoted as
saying in today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Since China started to carry out the policy of reform and
opening up policy in 1978, remarkable achievements have been made
in port facilities, said Zou.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China now has 235 state-level ports and 350
provincial ones.
</P>
<P>
Although China has enough ports, their comprehensive functions
have not been brought into full play due to unreasonable lay outs
and backward management, Zou said.
</P>
<P>
China plans to resolve the situation by regulating approval
procedures for new ports and reorganizing existing ones.
</P>
<P>
The state will merge some small ports which are close to each
other and close some ports which handle too little business, and
have poor economic returns.
</P>
<P>
As for improving port management, the state will concentrate on
completing trial port reforms in Shenzhen and introducing better
management in 30 ports where the annual handing volume makes up 80
percent of the total national amount.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
