<HEADLINE> Italy Sets up Task Force to Cope With Albanian Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government set up a task
force Thursday to deal with the 13,000 Albanians who have fled to
Italy since civil unrest broke out in the neighboring Balkan state
in February.
</P>
<P>
The government said in a statement that it had agreed to
proposals by the Association of Italian Town Councils (ANCI) to
"spread the refugee burden more evenly across Italy."
</P>
<P>
The ANCI said almost 6,000 of the refugees are in the southern
Puglia region, where more Albanians are still arriving despite
last Friday's shipwreck of an Albanian refugee boat in which more
than 80 were feared drowned after a collision with an Italian navy
ship.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the task force will be formed by
representatives from city and provincial governments as well as
interior ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
Among the mayors pledging their cities' support to the task
force was Rome's Francesco Rutelli. But several northern city
councils, notably Milan's administration, have refused to accept
any of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Milan's Mayor Marco Formentini said his "total blockade"
against Albanians was still in force.
</P>
<P>
In other government moves, Education Minister Luigi Berlinguer
said the ministry was preparing classes for refugee children and
planning to step up a cultural exchange program to help equip and
upgrade schools in Albania.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government has issued orders that the Albanian
refugees should only be allowed to stay for at most two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
