<HEADLINE> More Foreign Banks to Set Up Joint Ventures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- More and more foreign banks, which
have opened representative offices in Myanmar, are planning to set
up joint venture banks with its counterparts in the country in the
wake of Myanmar's entry into the second phase of its financial
reform.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, five foreign banks have signed memorandums of
understanding with local private banks to form joint ventures
including the latest one -- Cambodia's Global Commercial Bank
which reached a MOU on Thursday with Myanmar's Livestock and
Fisheries Development Bank, a state-private joint investment bank,
according to today's official newspaper the New Light of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The other four foreign banks, which signed MOUs earlier with
Myanmar, are Thailand's Farmers Bank and Siam City Bank, and
Malaysia's May Bank and Public Bank.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Fuji Bank Ltd formally entered into contract in January
this year with Myanmar's Yoma Bank, a private one, to jointly
operate banking business under the name of Fuji Yoma Bank, thus
becoming the first Myanmar-foreign joint venture bank in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In addition to six state-owned banks and some state-private
banks, there are 25 private banks in Myanmar now.
</P>
<P>
At present, the number of foreign banks that have
representative offices in the country have reached 44. They are
from 16 countries and regions and most of them are from Japan,
Thailand, France, Singapore and Malaysia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
