<HEADLINE> Italy Urges Greater EU Role in Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Italy today called for its European
Union (EU) partners to give "serious reflection" to mounting
tensions in the Middle East in hope of finding a way to push
forward the stalled peace process there.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry officials said that with the situation
deteriorating and violence escalating, the EU must find "new
diplomatic initiatives to be undertaken with the United States, to
help defuse the crisis and restart dialogue between the Israelis
and Palestinians".
</P>
<P>
Italy has asked the Netherlands, which holds the rotating
six-month presidency of the 15-member bloc, to call a special
meeting of EU foreign ministers to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
They said the first step toward saving the peace process was to
restore trust between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Italy has made numerous efforts to increase the EU's role in
the peace process. They include the measure leading to the naming
of the EU's special envoy to the region, visits to the region by
Prime Minister Romano Prodi and Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini,
and visits to Italy by Israeli Prime Mimister Benjamin Netanyahu
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Arab-Israeli relations have plummeted since late February when
Israel decided to build a Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem, a move that triggered a spate of violent conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League on Monday agreed to freeze relations with
Israel. Netanyahu's visit to Rome next week has been seen as an
important starting point on its road to recovering lost ground,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The EU's influence is underpinned by the fact that it accounts
for about 53 percent of foreign aid to the Palestinian National
Authority, and is Israel's biggest trading partner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
