<HEADLINE> Thai Airways Plans for Hike in Domestic Flight Fares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Airways International
(Thai) is planning for hikes in domestic flight fares, it is
confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
Confirming the fare hike plan, Thai senior vice-president Pisit
Kusalasaiyanon said the fare increase has been prompted by rising
oil prices, which have risen by 10 percent, and the weaker baht
against the yen and European currencies.
</P>
<P>
The national airline wants to increase fares by 200-300 baht
(8-12 US dollars) per flight because it expects to face higher
losses from domestic services this year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 Thai lost 40-50 million baht (1.6-2 million dollars)
from domestic flights and the amount is expected to jump to
300-400 million baht (12-16 million dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Transport and Communications Minister Suwat
Liptapallop said that his ministry will not consider a fare hike
now as Thai still enjoys 4,000-5,000 million baht (160-200 million
dollars) of annual profits from international routes.
</P>
<P>
In business terms, the Thai is still profitable, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
