<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China City Stopping Termites That Threaten River Dykes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Jinzhou, in central China's Hubei
Province, is waging a war against termites as the rainy season
draws closer.
</P>
<P>
The city on the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River
is in an area that gets plenty of rain. The low-lying land and
moist environment are ideal for the propagation of termites, and
37 percent of the urban area is infested with termites that
threaten river dykes as well as the ancient city.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government put extermination of termites on its
agenda years ago, and construction work units must include termite
prevention as part of infrastructure plans when applying for
permits.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, termite researchers cleared two million
sq m of building space of termites, and thanks to these efforts,
the city remained intact when it was hit by severe floods last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
