<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet's Economy Thriving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China's Tibet Autonomous Region's
GNP reached 6.45 billion yuan in 1996, an increase of ten percent
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time Tibet's economy has increased by double
digits.
</P>
<P>
For the ninth straight year, the region achieved a bumper
harvest in agricultural production, producing 779,000 tons of
grain. Meanwhile, its industrial output rose 14.4 percent on a
yearly basis, up 14 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the regional government also show that its
passenger transport volume and cargo transport volume went up by
25 percent and 27 percent, respectively, last year.
</P>
<P>
Also in 1996, Tibet's foreign trade soared by 65.2 percent to
more than 100 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
An official of the regional government attributed Tibet's
economic growth to the introduction of a modern enterprise system
and a joint-stock system, faster construction of basic industries
and efforts to promote agricultural production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
