<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flow in Upper Reaches of Yellow River Hits Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The flow on the upper reaches of
the Yellow River has hit a record low point, according to an
expert of the Yellow River Water Conservancy Committee.
</P>
<P>
The expert cited historical data to explain that the flow of
the river's section flowing through Lanzhou, capital of northwest
China's Gansu Province, decreased by nearly 33 percent in
comparison with the average level in the past.
</P>
<P>
Rainfall accounts for over 70 percent of the flow on the upper
stream of the Yellow River, which originates in the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau. The droughts on the plateau for several years running
have caused the river flow to remain relatively low since 1990.
</P>
<P>
According to Sun Meizhai, a senior engineer of the committee,
flow from the upper reaches of the river decreased by over
one-fourth in comparison with last year.
</P>
<P>
The Longyangxia Reservoir on the upper reaches of the river is
a major indicator of the flow from the upper stream. In the past
three months, the incoming flow was some 33 cubic m per second
less than the average level, reaching a record low.
</P>
<P>
The drop in water sources also caused the capacities of
Longyangxia Reservoir and Liujiaxia Reservoir, another reservoir
on the upper reaches of the river, to shrink drastically. The
designed capacity of the two reservoirs are 24.7 billion cubic m
and 5.7 billion cubic m respectively. Their present capacity is
2.49 cubic m less than that of 1954, a record low.
</P>
<P>
The river's section in east China's Shandong Province dried up
on February 7, seven days earlier than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River is the second largest river in China. But its
flow is less than five percent of the Yangtze River. The Chinese
Government is planning to divert the water from the Yangtze River
into the Yellow River to solve the water shortage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970404.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
