<P>
"The president in very strong terms will call upon the Senate
to ratify the Chemical Weapons Convention by the end of April when
the deadline for original adherence to the convention expires,"
White House spokesman Michael McCurry said today.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that the U.S. role in the enforcement and
implementation of the treaty will be severely restricted if the
Senate does not ratify the treaty by April 29.
</P>
<P>
"That would put us at a real loss of a leadership role as we
assure that other countries fully comply with the convention
itself, as we figure out ways to monitor and verify implementation
of the convention," McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, if the Senate failed to ratify the treaty before the
deadline, the U.S. would not be an original member in the
consultative committee that actually implements and monitors the
treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
