<HEADLINE> Apple Is Seeking Friendly Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The troubled Apple Computer Inc.
of the U.S. is actively looking for a friendly merger candidate,
according to local press here.
</P>
<P>
Prince Walid bin Talal of Saudi Arabia announced Wednesday that
he had paid 115 million U.S. dollars acquire slightly more than 5
percent of Apple during the last several weeks.
</P>
<P>
The news stirred some speculation about the fate of the
computer giant, which the prince believed to be able to recover
its past glory. The prince has become the company's largest
shareholder.
</P>
<P>
For Apple, Oracle Corporation's chairman, Larry Ellison, said
last week that he was considering, along with its partners,
spending more than 1 billion U.S. dollars to acquire Apple.
</P>
<P>
Apple, however, has a long and tangled history of failed merger
negotiations with other companies ranging from I.B.M. to the AT&AMP;T
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the company was probably in talks again with the
Sun Microsystems Inc., the California based work station maker
that came close to acquiring Apple last year.
</P>
<P>
Apple has lost 9.36 million U.S. dollars over the last five
quarters, and does not expect to make money again untile the fall
quarter, it is reported. The company chairman, Gilbert Amelio,
said that better times are only several quarters away since he
took the post a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the company laid off 4,100 employees, for which
it will take a 155 million U.S. dollar restructuring charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
