<HEADLINE> Mordechai Attacks Palestinians for Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai on Thursday laid blames on the Palestinians for
the recent violent clashes on the West Bank while deliberately
ignoring the fact that his government's violation of
Israeli-Palestinian peace agreements have caused a series of
protests staged by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters ahead of a meeting with U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen, Mordechai demanded Palestinian leader
yasser Arafat to take steps to "fight against terrorism," saying
that is "necessary" to push forward the peace process in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials have accused Arafat of giving a green light
to Palestinians' protests against the Israeli government's
decision to build 6,500 Jewish homes in east Jerusalem, which have
been evolving into violent clashes with Israeli soldiers rushing
to suppress.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai's remarks were a veiled repetition of those
officials' accusation.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli defense minister appeared to rule out any temporary
halt by the Israeli government of housing construction in east
Jerusalem, saying that Israel has its right to do so.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu vowed not
to relinquish the right to settle Jews in occupied lands when he
meet U.S. President Bill Clinton next week.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister will make clear in Washington that Israel
stands by its right to build in Jerusalem and in settlements, and
included in that the building will continue at Har Homa (on the
east Jerusalem hilltop)," Netanyahu's spokesman Shai Bazak said in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai is in Washington to discuss with his U.S. counterpart
strategic cooperation and anti-terrorist measures, including the
Arrow missile program, which Israeli has twice tested successfully,
and a high-energy laser, which could defend against Katyusha
rockets. 
</P>
