<HEADLINE> Cameroun: Dusk to Dawn Curfew Strictly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A dusk to dawn curfew has
strictly been implemented in six towns of North West Province of
Cameroun, the local paper "Cameroun Tribune" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The curfew was declared by Governor
Fai Yengo Francis on March 29, 1997 following armed attacks on
a number of military and civilian targets on March 27, 28 and 29
by armed individuals. The curfew prohibites the movement of people,
the holding of meetings and gatherings and the ban on fire arms at
funeral and other ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
Five days after the dusk to dawn curfew was imposed, the
residents in the six towns --Jakiri, Kumbo, Oku, Mbengwi, Bafut
and Bamenda -- are undertaking their daily activities unperturbed.
</P>
<P>
As from 5 p.m., people start rushing home after the day's
activities. Law enforcement officials then take to the streets to
enforce the curfew and search for the pepertrators of the
incidents on March 27, 28 and 29.
</P>
<P>
Movement in and out of Bamenda continues but not after 7 p.m.
when the gateway into the town from Bafoussam, the capital of
West Province, is closed to all vehicles. Travellers coming into
the town after that time spend the night at the gateway and can
only get into town the next day. Drivers who used to ply at night
from Bamenda to Douala, the economic capital of Cameroun and
Yaounde have ceased undertaking the late journey.
</P>
<P>
Social activities have been cut down to the barest minimum.
Most drinking spots no longer function at night.
</P>
<P>
Governor Francis has promised to lift the curfew as soon as
total calm returns to the province. enditem

