<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Big-name technology shares rose
on Wall Street today despite another downward turning of the broad
market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average lost 39.66 points to 6,477.35,
with little gains left for the years.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 12-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaled 495.47
million shares as against 478.14 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
But the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 list and the Nasdaq composite
index rose into positive territory.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 0.21 to 750.32, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 0.97 to 394.40.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 12.77 to 1,213.77, but is still
down about 6 percent for the year and off 12.5 percent from its
January high.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.37 to
557.82, and the Russell 2000 list of smaller companies fell 1.41
to 336.38.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's loss over the past five sessions amounted to about
400 points. Less than a month ago, the blue-chip barometer was
sporting a robust gain of about 637 points, or nearly 10 percent,
for the year.
</P>
<P>
Stocks remained under pressure from the bond market, where
long-term interest rates continued to rise to another six-month
high.
</P>
<P>
In a worrisome prelude to Friday's key report on U.S. payroll
and wage levels.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to slow economic activity and keep inflation under
control, Federal Reserve last week raised one of the central
bank's key lending rates higher for the first time in two years.
</P>
<P>
But if the strong economic data continued to be strong, the Fed
may decide to raise rates several times, potentially cutting into
company profits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
