<HEADLINE> U.S. Provides More Funds to Israel's Defense Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Pentagon announced on Thursday
that the United States has offered to provide more financial aid
to Israel's anti-missile defense program, including extra funds
for the joint U.S.-Israeli Arrow 2 anti-missile program and a new
laser weapon.
</P>
<P>
"The details aren't totally worked out, but we will increase
our investment in the Arrow missile program and will help with
testing and other aspects of it," Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon
said shortly after talks between visiting Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said current U.S. aid for the Arrow program, which stands
at about 200 million U.S. dollars over five years, might be
increased by as much as 25 percent after consultation with
Congress.
</P>
<P>
He gave no additional financial figures, but said the United
States had also offered to provide more money for joint work on
the U.S. "Nautilus" high-energy laser, which Israel intends to
use against Katyusha rockets.
</P>
<P>
Israel is currently developing the Arrow to shoot down Scud
and other missiles and Bacon said that Israel considered the
weapon very important to its defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
