<HEADLINE> Outlook for World Wheat Production in 1997/98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- World wheat production is forecast
at 583 million tons, or 3 million tons more than in 1996, on the
basis of information currently available, International Grains
Council(IGC) announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Larger crops are expected in China, EC and Ukraine, but reduced
sowings will probably curtail output in Canada and the United
States, IGC said.
</P>
<P>
Record harvests are unlikely to recur in Argentina and
Australia, but producers will again be influenced by international
prices over the next few months, it added.
</P>
<P>
International Grains Council emphasized that these forecasts
assume that normal weather will prevail throughout the growing
season.
</P>
<P>
Given the low volume of world stocks, weather news and its
effects on the production outlook, will remain an important factor
in determining the direction and stability of world prices, the
Council said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
