<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Consumer Borrowing Shows An Overheating Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
London, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Excessive credit card use pushed
net consumer borrowing in Britain to a record 1.22 billion pounds
(1.952 billion US dollars) in February, according to Bank of
England figures released today.
</P>
<P>
Net consumer credit in the month rose 17.5 percent on
year-on-year bases, the fastest rise since May 1989, the Bank
said.
</P>
<P>
Richard Jeffrey, group economist at Charter-house Bank, said
the figures were "truly staggering" -- similar to the growth in
consumer credit during the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
"You have to worry that consumer confidence is turning into
over-confidence," he added. "This has the makings of a highly
inflationary environment led by consumer spending."
</P>
<P>
Some economists in the City said that the rise was above market
forecasts and heightened expectations that interest rates would
need to rise to tackle an overheating economy.
</P>
<P>
The growth in consumer credit followed growth in earnings and
falling unemployment, which have boosted consumer confidence, they
added.
</P>
<P>
February saw the third-largest monthly fall in unemployment on
record, while the jobless rate fell to 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the latest wages figures showed a tightening labor
market and a 5 percent annual increase in earnings.
</P>
<P>
Don Smith, a economist at HSBC, said the increase in consumer
credit hardened the case for a rise in interest rates after the
general election on May 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
