<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Scientists Find Trigger of Heart Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists have found that
inflammation that smolders for years inside the arteries appears
to be a powerful trigger of heart attacks and strokes.
</P>
<P>
The new study, being published today in the New England Journal
of Medicine, is reported to be the first to show that the
inflammation is simmering, contributing to clogged arteries, while
those suffering from it appears to be healthy. Early study had
found signs of this inflammation at the time people suffered heart
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Although the cause of the inflammation is still unknown, a
leading theory is that chronic infection with common germs might
be the the reason, the New York Times said in a report. If so, the
report added, the study raised the possibility that antibiotics
and vaccines, along with stronger anti-inflammatory drugs, might
someday be added to the medicines routinely used to treat heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
The research also helps explain why aspirin is so good for the
heart. For years, experts thought aspirin's main benefit was
prevention of blood clotting. But the new study suggests that it
also works by fighting inflammation inside the blood vessels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
