<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Mortgage Rates Up to Near Seven-month High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Interest rates on 30-year,
fixed-rate mortgages in the U.S. averaged 8.18 percent this week,
the highest in nearly seven months, the U.S. Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp. said today.
</P>
<P>
It was a sharp increase from 7.97 percent the week before and
the gain put the rate more than a half percentage point higher
than the 7.56 percent average just six weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
The rates on 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages were the highest
since the 8.28 percent average during the week ended September 12
of last year.
</P>
<P>
On one-year adjustable rate mortgages, lenders were asking an
average initial rate of 5.80 percent this week, the highest since
the week ended September 26 and up from 5.71 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for those refinancing
mortgages, averaged 7.70 percent, up from 7.48 percent a week
earlier. It also was the highest since the week ended September
12.
</P>
<P>
Analysts on U.S. housing market have predicted that the market
would cool down this year because of higher mortgage rates but
remain strong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
